\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Agnes Beatrice Gilbey.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Married 1919 and born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 1897.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Could you tell me where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
I was born at Shelford, down by the river - a house named Water Hall. Those day of course it was - have somebody in the house - my grandmother used to go - round looking after children - 
well - she used to go right in the house, and she'd do all the housework, look after the mother and the baby, everything she would do. After she lost her husband just - that was her job. Um -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 That was your grandmother's house you mean, you were born i
n your grandmother's house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Water Hall was where I was born, yes. But my grandmother used to come down and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 She came down there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 How long were you living in that house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh that house was a - I - don't remember it you see b
ut - we moved - my mother and father moved from there - up to Hill farm, that's opposite the sand pit at Shalford. We was up there twenty-two years. Twenty-two years in that house. Married - I came here and we've been here ever since.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 So you were at Hill Farm from before 1900 really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Do I you know why they moved from one farm to the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Well, he - because it was a better house. Better house and - we - paid three pound a year rent, and had to find your own fireplace. That was it. Same as a fireplace - whatever fireplace you wanted you had to find yourself. Buy it yourself you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Bring the grate in and everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. Yes. Yes. Three pound, that was all we paid till we come up here wasn't it. Yes, three pound. Mm hm. That was my mother, that was the next door, and that's at - those - houses now have been made into two. And - it's a big - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid994437\charrsid14840390 sun door}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
 here now and - the other was - but it was very nice, and that was the photographer's bicycle there. An we used t
o get prize you see for the flowers. See my - mother's window was full of flowers. Used to get prizes for that, used to come round and judge you see. That's why this window's all full of flowers, I can't get out the habit of having flowers, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 How many rooms were there there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
It was - one room about the size of this, and a little - tiny kitchen, and - two bedrooms.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 And that's the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, that's the little kitchen window there, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 This is Hill Farm is it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes. Where - I went up to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 That's the farmhouse cottage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
And - that's - there used to be a pony - the man lived there used to have a - she'd, and used to be - have a pony and trap you see. But I that rose tree round that door is still down our garden,
 after all those years. And I was about - twelve when that photograph was taken, see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Is that you in the door there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, that's my mother there. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Who was it who lived in this house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Emily Ours, Miss Emily ours, she used to be ther
e. Then she went onto the telephone later on, but she used to live there with her mother, she used to do the dressmaking. Yes. She used to do dressmaking. But it's - you know, the old, the house now, it's been made - they've got bathrooms and that now of 
c
ourse but - still it - and we used to have a pump. Don't know if it was there the pump - I - I think my father had a row of sweet peas right round the pump, but there used to be a pump there. We was lucky to have the pump because other people used to have
 
to go miles to get water. Used to pump it with a handle like this to get it up. And up the road further, where Eva Grubb lived there used to be a well in the garden. A well, and they used to have a - chain on it, pail, and they used to have to turn a hand
l
e like this and the - you know, to get the water up. Then they used to have to lift the pail off the chain, and - and do it the same to get the water. Mm. But here - when we came here first - there's a well down here, and we used to have to go down and di
p
 the - pail in ourselves and lift the water up. Mm. Just out - it's still there now, at the moment, yes. But still we're on tap water now. We're on tap water now. 'Cos - we used to - on a wash day, it used to be amusing, we used to - we used to have to ha
v
e - baths of water, because there was - not sufficient water for - us - there used to be two houses here, it's pulled down. Didn't run fast enough - for us - to keep us all going, but it used to be lovely water though. Lovely water it used to be. It was y
ou know - just to get enough water to - do your washing in, and we used to have a copper. Of course that kitchen is pulled down now, used to have a copper and used to have a wood underneath and boil all your clothes in it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Is that the same when you were a child do you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Ever since I've been here. Yes. Oh I was about twenty then wasn't I? Twenty when I married, twenty-one, twenty-two, something like that. Mm. Twenty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 I didn't have no - bro
thers. Just myself. Mm. There was a little brother but he died when he was - tiny, my mother fell downstairs and - she - he died, he was born and he died. Mm. But - I was the only child. Mm. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Do you remember roughly when your father was born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
He was born, now, how old would he be? I should think he'd be - oh my mother'd be over a hundred - now wouldn't - my mother married when she was twenty-six. And she had the boy before I did. But my father was younger than my mother I think he was six yea
rs younger than my mother - when they married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Well that gives a rough idea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes it does.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 I was wondering what sort of age he was when you were a child really,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, it does, yes. If she was twenty - about twenty-six when I was - 
well, twenty-eight it would be wouldn't it, yes, He was a - a gardener, he was real gardener he was. He went up to Brentwood and always remember my mother had a terrible thunder storm, and it was some }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid994437\charrsid14840390 jubilee}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390  on I think, diamond jubilee, I remember my mother saying it thundered and }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid994437\charrsid14840390 lightened}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
 and it was terrible. Mm. She had only stopped up there six - months, then they came down to Shalford. He went up to learn the garden, the big place up at - there somewhere, I forget the name now. Yes, it - at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
Brentwood{\*\xmlclose}. Then he came back to Shalford and he stopped there ever since you see, he - was groom and gardener at Shalford Hall.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 He stayed all his life there did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes, stayed all his life, well nearly all his life, then he left at - Ling at Shalford Hall dyed and then he went and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid994437\charrsid14840390 worked}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
 in - Courtaulds factory, but he was never well after that, after being out in the open you know and then going into a factory he was never well. He died - my mother died when - she was fifty and my father died when he was just turned sixty. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What did he do in the factory at Courtaulds then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh he was in the dye factory, dye factory, yes. Didn't like it, no. Not after outside work. Yes. Well he married again you see but - I didn't care for his - my - new step
mother at all much. None too clean she wasn't. I couldn't understand my father because - my mother was very clean, she'd be all day doing her work, you know, everything had to be just so. Afraid I'm not quite like her but still - she was very clean and he
 went from one extreme to another you know, and - and I think it upsets one's life doesn't it, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did your mother ever have a job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, she always kept at home. She - she worked at the factory before she got married but - she never went out to work like they do of today, well I've been out to work for years haven't I Phyllis. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Where was this she worked, at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Braintree{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
City}}Braintree{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} mill that was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What did she do there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 I don't really know what she did do, weaver I suppose
 she was, I know it was Braintree Mill, 'cos it's - it's Courtaulds at Bo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10355869\charrsid14840390 c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 king ain't there and then }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid994437\charrsid14840390 there\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390  - the mills as well. The Mill she worked at, yes. They used to walk from Blackmore end to there, to work. Yes. Years ago they used to say, Blackmore
 End - when we was at Shalford, used to call Blackmore End High Ongar, Shal - Shalford they used to say Sharford. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Wethersfield{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 they used to say Wethersal. Finchingford the used to say Fingefor. That's how they used to pronounce the names like they really s
hould be. No. No. It's rather interesting how they - you know, especially the old ones how they used to say - I'm going now for me elevenses. That was eleven o'clock you see, they was going for the elevenses, or the four - the - four o'clock was fourses. 
Y
es. Yes, they used to say all sorts of things, yes. If you can sort of think of them you know. Mm. Well I used to go to my father - he used to have to help over in the harvest. I've still got the thing. They used to take quart bottles - take quart bottles
 of - beer, they used to - my father used to brew his own beer, down at the town office used to be - he used to take his own - bit - and they used to take that in the farm, that's very old.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Drink beer in the harvest fields over a hundred years ago?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What's it made of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
It's a horn, made of horn. Bullock's horn I think isn't it. Mm. I put it in the exhibition, that's why that's - papers still on it, it was on in the exhibition. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Where did you say that he made the beer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Down at tanoffice - Shalford there's - I don't know which way you come but there used to be an old brewer house down there and they used to take these casks, and they used to brew this beer, - and they always used to have to be ready for the harvest yo
u see. Yes, so they had to take the beer in the fields for the harvest, yes. And I'll tell you - used to be an old brewery up here, which is our village hall now. And - and the mens club too - and - is underneath the village hall, and I know my husband is
 going to do the tables, and they used to go down and they'd get how much did father used to say he used to get for tuppence? Gallon of beer for tuppence was it? I think so. Full gallon of beer. It's amazing isn't it? Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Was he brewing for a lot of people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, just for - each one used to brew their own beer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Where did you get the malt from then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
They used to - they used to have hops, they used - they used to buy these hops, they used to get the hops and - and then you - how they done i
t I don't know, but I remember as a child all this beer coming in you know. Great big casks, they used to have - bring it in the wagons you see, there used to be horses and wagons, used to bring it in and it used to be stood up in the - on a - it didn't u
sed to stand on the floor, it used to stand on like a stool, these big }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid994437\charrsid14840390 c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 asks did, you see, with a top in, and you used to go to it and that. Mm. Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 This was the congregational?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes. Yes. Yes - is it his son who's on the BBC, his grandson's
 on the BBC. Kenneth Adams. Mm. On the BBC he is. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 How would your father spend his day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Well he - he used to be - groom and gardener, he used to - see after the horse for Ling - Lings you see and then he'd - get 'em all ready and they'd go o
ut hunting. Sometimes he'd go on a hunt or two, and then - when he wasn't doing that he was in the garden you see. And then in the evenings when he was at home, well he used to do his own garden, and there used to be all these prizes for the best kept gar
d
en you see and - I remember one day - there was a man come round - and - to judge the garden, and he was a man in the village and they told somebody, they said to him, oh you can't - you don't know what old Bill Camber's garden's like today, he's had a bu
 
- he's had a bull in it. And - so they said, what? Poor old Bill, got a bull in his garden all ready to be judged. Of course it was the judge's name, Mr Bull. That was his name. So - it was a laughing over that. And that's my father that - had had an acci
d
ent you see, and he'd had a nail run in his foot and so he couldn't get about and - so they - they thought it was just dreadful you know, so they made fun of it. Had a bull in the garden. And that was the - the man's name, yes, but they always used to get
 first prize for his best kept garden. And this -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did he grow a lot of vegetables too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes, and the - I don't know where that photo is now of his collection of vegetables, you know, got first prizes for this and - we used to walk from Shalford, u
p to the Manor House here - with a great big washing bath all full, my mother, my - my father and myself - we used to be up at about three or four o'clock in the morning to get up here to get it all ready, judged, there used to be fruit that he - and ther
e
 was onions, and carrots and potatoes and cauliflowers peas, beans, oh that was a morning that was. Terrific tired when you got home at night. And we used to have a fair too over - just over here didn't we Bert, the fairs and - yes, Shalford one year and 
W
ethersfield one years, used to be the fairs were - and they used to have horses come you know and they used to parade round - oh I used to cry, because - when they - these horses had to dance, well years ago - they used to have shoes on and they used to h
a
ve spikes - spikes on their shoes see - like a little ring of spikes, and if the horses didn't do it properly they used to spike 'em and very often you could see blood come out. I used to cry, I used to say them poor horses. And yet I can't bear the horse
 
- I don't like horses, but I used - just used to cry because I couldn't bear to see them hurt you see. Yes. And then they used to have the Boy scouts, they used to do - bridges over the ditches and that, you know, for the - that was the day - every year t
h
at was, our show day, only - as you say it was Shalford and next year up here. Used to have the home - yes, that did. And - it used to be a day really that did, yes. And we only used to see bananas once a year. That was all, bananas, once a year, that was
 when - we - the - the fair used to come you see to these flower shows, they used to bring the bananas. But I tell you we did used to have fish didn't we Bert, once in a while - a man from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Braintree{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} used to come round. His name was - oh what was his name no
w? Don't know, used to come over in pony and cart, used to bring these bloaters harvest time. Then they used to be roasted in front of the fire and we used to take 'em into the harvest fields for them to eat you see for their tea. Like that. Mm. Sharpley 
was the fishmonger's names wasn't it, Sharpley, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 How often did you have meat then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. Oh meat. Oh about once a week that was all. Once a week meat. And mother used to make these lovely meat puddings, I can see 'em now, in the cloth. They u
sed to be - all made in a cloth, rolled out, made - all meat puddings, they went in a cloth. And that, that used to last for a couple or three days you see and then we used to have a bloater one day for dinner - and all - perhaps what - another day a piec
e of bacon you see, and used to make these - little dumplings you see with bacon rolled in, be nice. Onion pudding too, yes, had it with the gravy you see. Yes. And that used to be healthy food I mean, the - it was not - not make up like it was now, no.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Any tinned food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, no tinned food. No tin, no. Yes, Nestles Milk was about the thing in tin, yes. Yes. Nothing else was tinned, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Could you tell me the meals of a typical day, what would you have for the beginning of the day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Well fo
r breakfast we - we was lucky - sometimes because we kept our - chickens you see. And - we used to have a egg for breakfast, and - cup of tea and that but some children only had bread and dripping you see. Then for dinner we used to have this - always use
d
 - my mother used to make dumplings very often if we hadn't got any meat or anything, dumplings and we - we used to have butter on them or - or - we used to have butter but some children used to have - about - nothing much on 'em you see, used to eat them
 
as they was and potatoes. We'd plenty of vegetables those days. And then tea we used to have bread and butter, and - cake once a week, that was all, have say a bit of cake on the Sunday. That was all. But - otherwise I mean it was all good food really. Mo
t
her used to make - rice, we used to have - get this skimmed milk, we used to have rice puddings - like that. And they used to make 'em years ago so you could cut them. And used to have them - with a little bit of jam on them see. Used to be - made in a bi
g - dish like that, then used to cut a slice out you see and used to eat them like that. Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did she have a range to cook on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Well - I don't know if you'd call it a range, it was just a fireplace with an oven at the side. Just a fire, a little o
ven at the side. And the food used to taste better then they do now with this electricity. Way it was cooked. In fact we had one - here - here. Back of that, yes. And - this has been in now about thirteen - used to cure all the hams. There's great big hoo
ks up there, used - where they used to - cure the hams, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did your mother cure any hams like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. Yes. They used to keep the pigs. Mm. And they'd go - I don't now how far too if anybody'd got a spare pigs belly. I've seen my mother stand
 there - or sit hours and I used to have to help, used to clean all the inside out, wash it and that used to last for - coo, I don't know how long. These pigs bellies, you know, used to - boil 'em and then they used to - fry 'em afterwards and they used t
o make jolly good dinners like that, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 So you kept a pig in the garden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 And hens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Nothing else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Rabbits, I used to have a rabbit, yes. Oh rabbit, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Not to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, wouldn't eat the - no, 
we used to get rabbits off the firled. That was another meal. The poor people years ago, they - used to be allowed to go and catch the rabbits, used to snare them years ago, make a snare. And - put 'em in the ground each - and in the mornings you see the 
-
 they used to get up early, go and see if these - a rabbit in the snare, and - my mother used to roast 'em lovely in the oven, they used to - she - we liked 'em better roasted than anything. You'd - joint 'em up, and - roast 'em like you would a chicken, 
they used to be jolly nice done like that. Mm. Some onions and that you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Nobody minded them catching the rabbits?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, no, no. No. No, didn't mind those days, no. No. But it wouldn't do to touch a pheasant, you could get run if you touch a pheasant. 'Cos there used to be lots of rabbits about years ago you see, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did she bottle any fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, no, we didn't know no bottling things. No. No. We used to always expect rhubarb feast, something missed out - if that wasn't right if we d
idn't have a rhubarb pie feast - for Easter, and Whitsun, we used to have to have a gooseberry pie for Whitsun. That was the - that was the main thing. Those two - Easter and Whitsun, when - they - they were the two things, rhubarb and - gooseberries. If 
you hadn't got it then oh well it was dreadful. He was no gardener.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What about bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, my mother never did bake bread because we'd never anywhere where there's a bread oven. But your mother used to didn't she? She'd got a bread oven, but - the
 house we lived in we hadn't got a bread oven. No. So we used to have to - buy the - we used to go out gleaning of course and get the flour and we used to - have all the puddings and that and they used to be nice, the - the - the flour, although it was da
rk, the puddings used to be lovely and sweet. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Where did you get the wheat ground?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
We used to - after the harvest you see - all the - you daren't go in a field while there was a sheaf of corn in the field. When that sheaf was took away you co
uld go in and glean what you want. And - after - after they'd raked it and of course years ago you see - there was no combines then like there is now, well they used to - lot of the - used to be about a dozen work on a farm, I used to go all round the out
s
ide - and cut the - bit about that wide to get the - what did they call - binder in. Binder in and then they'd go round and round and - put the sheaves out wouldn't they, and they used to collect them, all used to go to the farmyard, all make these sacks,
 
my father used to be - stack - he used to stack all these up and they used to have to be thatched. Well then, after that was done and they'd got the gleanings out then we was allowed in and we - used to go over all the field and pick these ears of corn wh
a
t they used to drop you see and of course there used to be lots in the fields and we used to tell each other when there was a field ready and away we'd go. Well then we used to cut the ears off, just the ears, used to have these sacks of - ears all in the
 
- she'd outside, then when there's a traction engine used to come by the vicarage - one man only had one field, and he used to have this traction engine come to - thrash his corn out, well - all us in the village used to take all our sack so corn up and t
h
ey used to do it for us you see, like that. And then they used to be took down to Wethersfield Mill and ground - after we got the wheat used to be ground, we used to have the flour, 'cos it wasn't dressed then like it is nowadays, all white and that, inst
ead it used to be jolly nice. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 I think it's better for you isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes. Not - all those chemical things. Mm. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did your mother make any medicines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 I'll tell you what I used to have to do. My father had a row of - lilies.
 Madonna lilies they were called then, right down the path - and - as soon as heads ones - dropped off I used to have to gather these lily leaves for my mother. She used to put 'em in Bovril bottle. These lilies - leaves were covered with brandy, and if y
o
u fell down and - or cut yourself you had to have a lily leaf took out of this brandy and put on, and that was good as iodine you see. Yes. You - did you used to do that Bert for your mother? That's the only thing I can - that's the only thing - that's th
e
 only thing I can remember that my mother used to do. Mm. Oh and - the bulace too. We - she - we - if she had bulace - in the garden, we used to get those bulaces, get 'em in a jar, big - casserole they call them nowadays, but they - they called 'em jars 
years ago, put 'em in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid994437\charrsid14840390 oven}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
, just stew them. And if you had a bad cold, that used to - supposed to help your cold. Oh and also too if you had a bad cough, mother used to always give me - a tablespoonful of vinegar and honey, mixed together like that and 
I used to have to swallow that for a bad cough. That's all - and - we never used to bother the doctor like they do nowadays at all, I mean we used to - just have a bad cough used to have your honey and vinegar and that was that. 'Cos my father used to kee
p bees you see so we had plenty of honey, yes. Yes, he used to keep bees.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 In the garden as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes, in our garden, I've taken a - a swarm of bees myself. One day he was out - now, Agnes, he said, you watch them bees - won't you? I said, yes, da
d, I'll watch your bees. And - I never saw them swarm but I went in and out at times and there they was on the - inside the gardens at home and he said you never watched them bees for me today. I said, I did. He said, well you come here and look, and ther
e
 was a swarm of bees. He just took 'em like that. Well one day he was out and - got several hives, I thought, oh dear, I suppose I shall have to look at those bees again. And I watched em and they went over in the field. I thought, whatever am I going to 
d
o if they go away, my father will be cross. I got a hat box, we used to have these - square boxes years ago, hat boxes, and I got this hat box - and I got - and I got 'em in, I hadn't got nothing over me at all, I got them in that hat box and stood that b
o
x down. And do you know, when he came home at night they'd started - to make the - wax. Yes. He said, do you mean to say you done that yourself? I said, yes, I did. I said, I was a bit nervous when I done it. Yes. And - you know, it was exciting days real
l
y I mean - you never used to see the - loll about the roads like they do now in those days, they always had something to do. There was always work to be done. And they used to go and help peo - people, you know, everybody was good enough to go and help ot
her people but - they - you can't get them - today, not like -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What sort of help do you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Well if anybody wanted their garden dug the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid994437\charrsid14840390 young}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
 boys'd go anywhere to earn a penny but you can't get them now after tea to go and earn a penny can yo
u? They'd rather - got to cinemas or go and do mischief or something, yes. But year ago they'd go anywhere to earn a penny. Mm. Well when I started work first I mean I had a half a crown a week. Yes. And I saved that up and then I walked to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Braintree{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} as - 
you saw in the - thing and brought me bicycle and wheeled it home. And that was at - when I was fourteen that was. And me father learnt - started to learn and he seemed to - got halfway up the road and then he let go of the bike and down I went. I said, o
h the bike. He said, you've got to learn - learn - look you'll never learn 'til you fall off once. That was me new bike, but it didn't hurt it anyway. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Were you allowed to talk during meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh no, not much, no. No, we had to be very silent. T
hey used to have to sit still at night too, you know, in your chair and that. Mm. Well we used to do needlework or knitting and - my mother used to make - mens shirts for tenpence each, and I used to have to take all the tackings out for her you see. That
 
machine is still her machine and it's still in working order. Just as good as ever it was. But it - it - that's over a hundred years old, but - I still use it but I can't get the needles now, I'm on the last needle and they won't let you - they don't make
 them needles now you see. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Where did she make the shirts for then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
For - there was a family with - how many was there - nine boys, nine boys in family, and she used to make the shirts for all them boys, and they used to be lined, not like the
y are now - all - they all had to be lined here, and - she used to make these shirts for tenpence and there used to be - they - she used to make about four a year I suppose, 'cos they used to last those days, the material used to last you see. 'Cos they o
nly had - a - only had one shirt a week, no more than one shirt a week ever. '{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Cos{\*\xmlclose} of the washing. Fetching of the water. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did she make your own clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
She make my own frocks, yes, they used to be made out of other peoples. Mm. Sometimes I used to get new frocks, yes. Well -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Where did you get the new ones from then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Used to have to walk to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Braintree{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Yes, have to walk - had to walk to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Braintree{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. But the little red coat that I wore at the coronation, I always remember that because it was all red, that was a brand new one. That was a red co}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid994437\charrsid14840390 a}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
t - King Edward - VII I suppose that would be would it, any rate - this red coat that had these buttons on it you know, and then I had a little black - velvet hat, and it used to have a little tiny }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid994437\charrsid14840390 squirts}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390  hang down there. I remember that. We used to always have these }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid994437\charrsid14840390 coronation}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
 mugs. Yes, for ever - for - I think there's still one here now. A - a mug. Years ago. On horseback then - they got - they had - the Wethersfield Hall over there for the doctors you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 The doctor lived in the Hall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. Wethersfield Hall, yes. Used to come round with a cart when he got - come home with a car, and - oh dear - one day I had the measles and I was so afraid of the doctor coming you know, and then he t
ook me - took me on me - oh his lap, and I was so pleased he took me on his lap, he said, oh - he - spoke about my hair, 'cos I did used to have nice hair when I was young, I used to sit on it, well you can see there - and - I was so pleased 'cos - he say
s
, but what have you got on your hair? So I said, well - my mum - my mum hadn't prepared me quite for you to come, she was going to put a bit of ribbon on but I got a shoestring - on - If we saw a policeman coming or anything we used to - sort of hide, we 
u
sed to be so afraid of a policeman years ago, I mean now they don't take no notice at all do they. And - one day - as I come home from school there was a policeman going in my - mother's gate. Oh dear, what's my mother or father done now? And I stood out 
i
n the road crying. And - then he came out again and I went in, mother said, you have been a long while coming home from school. Well, I said, there was a policeman indoors, I didn't know what he was doing. So she said, he only came in and had a glass of w
i
ne, that was all. He - he was thirsty and he come in and dad - my dad was home, and - because they used to be friends together, well I didn't sort of realize it. When I saw the policeman he used to be in his ordinary clothes you see, well when he went in 
with his helmet and that on I was afraid, but - any rate - I soon got used to him going in and out because he used to pop in and out to get the - a drop of homemade wine or a glass of beer you see, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Your mother made wine then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, oh always }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid994437\charrsid14840390 homemade}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
 wine, yes, rhubarb wine. Rhubarb wine or - whatever was going in the way of - wines you see, always. Used to be - oh - used to - there used to be prizes at the flower show you see for the homemade wine, the clearest and all that, that used to be -
 there used to be the thing, the homemade - who could make the best wine. And all like that. And jam too. Used to make all her own - never bought a bit of jam, no, always used to make it out of the garden. Same as vegetables - the same - well if you hadn'
t got enough }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid994437\charrsid14840390 potatoes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
 for the year you used to go round and see somebody else - if they got - could allow you enough - you had to - have your own stock of things to last a year, 'cos you - they'd never have them - have them in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid994437\charrsid14840390 ships}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390  like they do now you
 see. And if you knew anybody got any apple trees away you go and buy a bushel of apples. Store them - in - straw or something you see, to keep for the year, otherwise you'd never could get an apple. No, you couldn't get an apple. No. They never had them 
i
n the shops you see. Still there we are. And we used to have a lovely pear tree too. And that - that's still in the garden, the same age as I am, my father brought it - up from Water Hall and put it in the garden and Shalford and it's still there, what we
 
used to call Old Woman pears years ago, I don't know what the real name is to these, used to be called Old Woman pear, they used to be jolly nice pears too. Yes. And me mother used to stew them as well, you see, stew them, 'cos they didn't keep very long,
 
that was the trouble. So we have them stewed and eat them, yes. And there's nuts the same, we used to go round the hedges and gather nuts. Yes. Used to gather nuts. But of course now you see all the hedges are cut down. Yes. Yes, we used to have fun reall
y
 those days, in - in the - used - I don't know, used to be something to do, anything. Yes. And then we used to see these horses come by - all dressed up. Stallions you see. And - they used to have the ribbons all on them and that, they used to look lovely
 years ago really they did. Of course now you see they're all }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid994437\charrsid14840390 go in}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390  lorries. These stallion horses used to - well they was a - picture. I think I've still got - oh no, my husband - oh no, here it is, down there - horseshoe look - I found - found in the road
, I never would part with it and it's still there, I don't know how old it is but - it's ever so old. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Were those horse brasses anything to do with your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh yes. They're {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}Victoria{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} you see to - that's to - to do with my husband's - people they are. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Not your father?
