 get butter - and that was a job to get butter and a job to get cheese 'cos nothing was rationed then what it was the second world war, and - I went home one day and I said to mother, I said, look, I've found you a half a pound of margarine. Oh, she said,
 
how lovely, but, she said, your dad'll never eat it, he'll never eat margarine. I said, try him, say nothing to him about it. Say nothing. She cut the bread and butter, put it - it were good this margarine, it's Blue Band now, put it on the table. He ate 
i
t. So after he'd finished I said, oh did you like your bread and butter dad? Yes, he said, it - that was lovely. So I said, oh I thought you never was going to eat margarine in all your life. I - I said, you've been eating margarine. I never have, he said
.
 I said, you have. I said, I've had you there for once haven't I? And then - you see, when we used to have our birthdays we used to have the children - each family - what we used - a little round of friends we used to have, we used to go to their birthday
