done by next - next exhibition, yes. Same as I use scraps - my mother too used to - every day we was born she'd - make a little pair of shoes, baby's shoe socks she used to call them with berleen wool, and you couldn't beat the at wool. Lovely wool that w
as. Every - she would used to do that, and if anybody ordered a pair that used to be tenpence a pair. To make them and the wool too. 'Cos things were so much different then, we had a ha'penny a week pocket money. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you always have a ha'penny?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What did you spend it on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes, ha'penny pocket money. Oh - we used to go and buy a few - you know, sweets, well we used to get a - - quarter of a pound I suppose for about a ha'penny, a quarter of a pound. The - banana creams, I've neve
r tasted a sweet like it, we used to go - to this house - they used to just sell these - nothing else but sweets, and Lipton's tea he used to sell, and there used to be banana creams, and they used to be lovely. Shape of - not so big as that but - that ki
nd of shape, like - like that. And oh they used to be lovely those banana creams. Used to get a quarter - quarter of a pound I suppose for about a ha'penny. Mm. I mean we used to get a lot for the little money we had those days. Yes. We did.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did your father ever take you out just by yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Not very - much because there was nowhere much to go you see. We used to have to go to church every Sunday, oh yes, church every Sunday used to sit there quiet as a mouse and - I always remember - both of us
 was at church, my mother, father and myself, of course my grandmother came in, and I said, oh look mum, there's gran - granny there. Oh - oh I had a smack for that, talking in church you know. Yes. Yes. Oh we always had to go to church on Sundays 'cos if
 
you didn't go to church on the Sunday - you'd have the sack you know. Yes. Oh - on - go on the carpet, why wasn't you at church on Sunday? And my father - you know - he used - where - why wasn't you at church and that, 'cos you - now you see there it is,;
 they don't take much notice now do they -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Who would say that to him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
The farm - farm - who he worked for, yes, and - Abbots Hall used to be Squire Marriott to - oh he used to go all round, why wasn't you at church and that. And - oh he wasn't ve
ry well or something, you be sure you'll be there next Sunday you see. Church used to be full of people, yes. More than they dare do, was not go to church. I used to be in the choir when I got old enough, used to wear white - straw hats with just a black 
b
end round the girls did, and the boys - boys and the men used to wear surplices like they do now but - then we - on a Friday was choir practice, dinnertimes, this was at - after - we - school was at twelve o'clock and he had to be back again at half past 
o
ne - we used to have to walk up to Abbots Hall which was a mile, do our choir practice, walk back again to school. In that - dinner - dinner time and we used to have a cake, slice of - lump of cake and glass of milk, for going up there to - sing in the ch
oir. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you go to Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. Sunday school we used to - there used to be little old tin church at - Jasper's Green. We used to go up - there in the afternoon, and then in the morning we used to go - to Shalford, it's named the Firs 
now, it used to be a little - they used to have like a wash house, we used to have to go in there in the morning. Twice a day Sunday school. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 And the church service?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes, we did, yes, we used to have prize books you see for best attend
ance and all like that. Day school the same. Mm. And then the attendances used to be put in - so many attendances.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Was that a chapel Sunday school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. I used to go to church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 They were both church Sunday schools?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. There used to 
- I don't think there was a chapel Sunday school. I can't remember there was. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 I wondered why it was at Jasper's green did you say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes, well there used to be a - a Mar - Squire Marriott built - built that little tin - tin church up there. Bu
t since then there is a chapel one. But - since I've - left Shalford there is a real chapel - church up there now. Yes. But I don't think there was when I was a child, I can't remember it. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did they go on Sunday school outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Well not 
on outings, we only had the bit - Squire Marriott's at Abbots Hall. We used to go in and have all our tea together - all on a long - trestle table. It was having the tea together that made the fun, we used to have - used to call it pudding cake really, lo
v
ely all big - slab of cake nearly as big as this table as you might say. Or about - half that - size like that, and it used to be all currants and that, the cook used to make it you see and we used to have bread and butter and this cake, we - then we used
 
to have p games, we used to have to run they used to chuck a handful of sweets all on the grass, those days. Used to have to run and see who could pick up the most you now. All like that, then we used to have skipping and marbles and - all like that, and 
t
hen we used to have tickets to go on the lake, there used to be a lake. And boats, and we used to have a ticket -, we used to take it in turns. And I went on one day - this school treat, I forget how may boys was in that boat, they rocked - oh - didn't I 
s
cream, the water nearly coming inside and I've never been able to go on the sea since, that frightened me so much, even to this day I daren't go on the sea. No, I just - I don't know why it gave me such a scare as a child, and I just - didn't - couldn't g
o on a ship or anything, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Was there a Band of Hope?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No. No band of Hope. My father used to have a - there used to be a Primrose League - for the men. Primrose League. Used to have. He - he joined that after a while, and - said he wouldn't 
drink no more beer or anything - no I'm afraid I haven't got it, the badge - and - that used to be - a thing they used to go to. He gave up - smoking, he gave up - drinking and - I don't think he was ever so well after he - he gave that up, it was an inte
rest you know. Yes. Thought I had a Primrose - League button, yes, I have still go it. All those years ago - they joined that. Primrose League. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 When would that be, do you know?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh that was - here - I should think I was about fourteen then. 
Yes. When he gave up smoking and that. I went out in the garden one day and I found his pip it was perched in a faggot of wood you see, and I said, to my mother, ooh, I've found dad's pipe what he - he's gone to work without his pipe today. Oh, she said, 
h
aven't you noticed, he hasn't smoked for a long time. So I said, no. So she said, no he hasn't smoked. And - I said, pph, and I - of course I took it indoors and - she said, no, he hasn't smoked now, hasn't drank anything for a long time. And I think join
ing this Primrose League that was all the - time in those days these things was, and he never did drink or anything - all after then, why don't know, but I've always kept that in remembrance of him. And he - when I found his pipe and that. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Were there any other sort of clubs to do with the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No, well there used to be the Mothers {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}Union{\*\xmlclose} then used to go to, Mothers Union. But the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did your mother go to that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, she used to go to that, yes. But there was nothing - like there
 is of today same as friendship clubs or - anything like that, no. No, don't remember anything like that. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did your parents think it wrong to work or play on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh, we daren't do - anything in a Sunday, oh dear, no, we used to have to s
it still like this, we didn't have to - do anything on a Sunday at all, no. If - oh, if we - we'd touched a - and you didn't have to play a game of - dominoes or anything like that, not on a Sunday. Oh no. I know my - grandmother came up when I had my fir
s
t baby here. And - she came up and looked after me, this was in - 1920 this was - she came up and I was doing a little bit of needlework, oh child, she said, you mustn't do that on a Sunday, she said, you'll have the devil with you all the week. That was 
my grandmother. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Your mother and father were very religious?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes, they were, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did they have prayers in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, we didn't have prayers, we didn't go to that, no, but we always had to go to church - 'cos we used to ha
ve prayers at school you see, as soon as we got to school in the morning there was prayers you see. We used to have prayers and - and I had to say me prayers at night before I went to bed. Oh yes, I had to go - fall on me knees and say me prayers - before
 I went - to sleep, yes. Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Grace at meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, no, we didn't always have grace at meals. But always had to say me prayers. Mm. Whatever - I was just trying to think what I used to have have to say. God bless daddy mummy, granddad - grandma, au
nts, uncles, cousins and all good - all - unkind friends and all good friends. For Jesus Christ's sake, amen, I think that's what it was I used to have to say - every night bar none.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you have special clothes on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Special clothes, 
yes, we used to have this - special frock on a Sunday. Used to have a - a - never used to be - used to - didn't get soiled like they do nowadays, 'cos we - I suppose we didn't used to do what they did. No. And then - and then we used to wear pinafores you
 see but - these white pinafores used to last - had to last the week. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Your mother would be upset if they got dirty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Mm, yes, they would, yes. Yes. Yes she would, mm hm. I remember once she telling me when I was a child - she - it was very - 
there was ice on the ponds and that and there was a pond just down the bottom of the road and if there's a lot of children on it, she said, now don't you do - dare go near that pond will you. Aggie, so - she said, not to go on it. I said, no, mum, I won't
 
go on it. Well all the other children was on the pond and there I stood you know. And I thought dare I go on it. And there's a - at the side of the pond it's never so - icy as it is really in the middle, I just put one foot and -- dashed if it didn't - go
 
in the water, and boot - oh I got - sodden my foot and - did, I thought whatever shall I do? And I never I - I never really went on it so I got indoors and mum said, you're not taking your shoe - your boots off tonight? So I said, no. I'm all right, I'm n
o
t tired tonight. But I sat there with this shoe - like this, I daren't say a word. And it gradually got dry you see by the fire. And - then at last I did take it off, but - oh dear, if she'd have seen it I'd have to take a hiding. Yes, I should, I should 
h
ave - I should have had the - it was a lonely life really those days being an only child because I lived up there - that house there, and there's no other houses near me for - oh half a mile a mile, and I had no playmates at all, I had to make me own - I 
used to go and sit hours with my rabbit and talk to the rabbit you know. Yes, and used to go and get the food for it. Yes. But as for - do - if you done anything wrong, oh dear, weren't you in for it. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 How did you feel about being punished like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh I used to cry for hours. I only remember once my father hitting me and only once he did hit me. Oh and I never got over it for days, he hit me on the back like that. And - I don't know -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 It was usually your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. I don't know
 what - I can't remember quite but I think I told him a fib or something, and - he found out. And - didn't I go through it too. Said, you dare to do that again. Oh I said I hadn't been somewhere and I had, I remember now. I said, I haven't been anywhere. 
H
e said, I told you never to go near that place again, you know, they was - rather strict with me. I suppose they - be - being an only child they was more stricter with me than there'd been more you see. They - after losing the - other baby, they thought I
 might - they might lose me I think. Mm. Yes. But otherwise it - you know, I never did - much wrong really. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 If you had any worries could you talk to them about them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh they, yes, if it was the school or anything, yes, oh sometimes I used to 
go home crying. They'd say, what are you crying for? I said, mum, there weren't half a boy thrashed at school today. And I could feel those thrashes you know, and say - she's said, well why worry, she said, it - it - as long as you wasn't being thrashed a
t
 school it was all right. Mm. Schoolmasters was very strict years ago to what they are today. Yes. Very strict they were. Mm. I mean you daren't hardly turn your head at school than what you wasn't - sort of told about it. Mm. No, there it is. Or if you s
poke - whispered to anybody, you was told off in a minute, yes. If you done it the second time then you had the cane.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 The girls as well you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. Girls as well as boys, oh yes. Yes, that made no difference. No. 'Cos one boy - oh he was a nau
ghty boy at school really, but he used to - have the cane, oh across his hand and that, and he - it didn't used to worry him but - oh, I could feel it when that cane come down, you know. Yes. Yes. And used to have - little plays at school too. We used to 
h
ave concerts, you know, we used to - have to act and that and do recitations and things - songs and that, that's about - what we used to do at school. Mm. Then we started dancing. We had a new schoolmaster come, his name was Hiscock and then we started to
 learn dancing at school, and - oh I left school soon after then so I couldn't keep it up. Used to have the Lancers and the quadrilles and the - Valetta. What was the other one? Don't know. But still -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What did you say about the puddings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh the 
pudding - oh the puddings, we - we always used to eat them before the meat, the - onion pudding with the gravy, and then we used to have the vegetables afterwards you see. Same with - but not with the - sweet pudding, not with the sultana pudding, but the
 onion pudding and the other light pudding, used to have. If there were - if there was anything I left out.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 I didn't know if I asked you where your father came from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh no, you didn't, no, well he came from Shalford. He was - born at Shalford bu
t my mother was born at Blackmore End. And - she used to work - I told you before at the mill. My father was at Shalford and there was - nine of them. I - grandmother was left quite a widow you know and she brought all them up, all the nine children up. D
o
n't know - how many aunts and uncles I had but any rate the were all right, and then she - after she lost my granddad she used to go out nursing you see. Right into people's houses, and - do all the work of the whole lot, family cooking, everything. Mm. Y
es.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Apart from the harvesting work did your father do any other sort of part time jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No. Because they always had to work all hours you see then. You couldn't do no part time jobs them days because the hours were so long. See? I mean you - 
just had the one job and that was it. Yes. Couldn't work no - no other - jobs at all. No. Not - I mean same as now you can can't you? The hours are not so long, I mean they used to start work at six. And never left off 'til six at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Your father came home at six at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes, six o'clock you see and then they used - he used to have his tea, well then he used to do his own gardens. Of course winter time is sawing up wood. Yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 In the house there was just you and your mother and fathe
r and nobody else living there, no lodgers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No, no lodgers, no, no lodgers, no, only just the - us three, that's all. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 So you slept in a bedroom by yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. I had a bedroom by myself. Only a little tiny bedroom, just enough f
or a bed, and enough for - a box, years ago you see they didn't have the furniture like we do now, it was just a - orange box, papered over with the wallpaper. You just have your belongings in there. See? Yes. We didn't have the furniture, and - we was be
t
ter off than some 'cos my mother had - coconut matting over the floor, but some people only had - the bare bricks and they used to put sand on them. They used to look - be all right, but it was not warm you see, not like a - we used to have the coconut ma
tting those days but - talk about the dirt go through it though.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 So she did all her own housework?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes, she done all her own housework, yes. Same as for washing outside - we used to have a big old boiler - years ago, big old boiler - stood on br
icks, and we used to have the wood underneath to make the - put the sheets and that in, used to - boil it up like that you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You did that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 That's once a week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Once a week that was, yes, once a week, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 And you'd have clean clothes once a week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes, once a week, only once a week. And it was - it was the - it was always a - flannelette - petticoat we had, not a flannelette, a flannel petticoat, and it's generally red, red flannel petticoat. And - our knickers wa
s all embroidered mostly by hand and - stays, always used to wear stays. We always used to have to have a piece of flannel - inside here to keep our chests warm, so we shouldn't have colds. Yes. That was our - things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you have a weekly bath night or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh yes, in front of the fire. In front of the fire. With our wash tub - what - a bath what we used to wash the washing - in you see. There was a big - bath with just two handles. Used to be in front of the fire the bath - if it was very
 cold - we had a wash down. Well nowadays they'd call it bunget bath wouldn't they, you see, used to - just with a bowl of water and - used to wash you down from top to bottom. Yes, we used to keep quite clean really. Mm. Yes. That's what - that's how we 
used to wash 'cos our faces and hands and - feet were all washed more often but not the boy part itself. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You did mention something about shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
The shoes. Well we had boots, always boots. Always boots, and I had - weekdays we had a pair for w
eekdays and a pair for Sundays. And always had these heel irons on. It was about - half inch thick like that, the - top heel of the leather you see, and then used to have studs in here. Just studs and they used to last all the winter, like that. But Sunda
y
s we used to have a pair with no kneel iron. And no studs, and they used to be - look - rather fancy, there were more fancy work with the toe cap, always a toecap on it, yes. Otherwise that was all what we had. And even - when my children were small, they
 
had boots too, I mean - they're fifty years old they are. They even had - boots then. See - it's only - it's only lately that - well, I say - I know how long ago it was that they did start shoes but it was always boots. You can't see the children wearing 
boots now can you.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Where did you buy the boots?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. Always used to buy the boots. I mean they used to be made of all leather, I mean now it's all - rubber kind - in - rubber and that, yes, all leather, and my father used to do the heels. Himsel
f. Used to have a - iron - thing you know, used to put the boots on, he used to always do - put his own studs in himself you see if they come out he used to put his own studs in himself. And the heel irons too he did put on, you could buy them - and put t
hem on. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you buy them in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Braintree{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, you had to walk to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Braintree{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} to get them. Once a year walk to Braintree, we used to save up the whole year, walk to Braintree and my mother and I would, and - if we - she wanted anything special, s
ay - a coat or - anything or - piece of material or anything had to walk to Braintree to get it. Well then gradually it got - there was a man came out from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Braintree{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} with all these things on a bicycle. See, so it spared us - going into Braintree, you could
 buy towels off of him, and - tea clothes, sheets, anything and he'd let you - if you hadn't got quite enough money he'd let you - pay it the next time. See? You see, yes, and his name was Shinfield. He lived in - Square - Patrick Shop now I think in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Braintree{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Mm. He was very good he was, it - that was his father and then the son took on and I see the son in the paper the other days has died. Mm. But of course - and calica then was only fourpence ha'penny a yard. Fourpence ha'penny a yard. And now look at 
it. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You didn't have those travelling men selling the cloth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No. No. We don't - we wasn't - the only thing we used to have occasionally was a black man used to come round you know about - selling stuff, and he used to be so cross if you didn't buy anything off of him. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What was he selling?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh - beads and, you know, all like that. Yes. And - all silk handkerchiefs, that kind of stuff. You didn't buy anything he was cross. We used to be sort of half afraid of him when he come 
round, 'cos they have these turbans on you know. Yes. Yes. Yes. They do come round her now occasionally, but not so much as they did. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 When you say you saved up the money, did you have a savings club?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, we used to have a box, just a bo
x, with a little lock to it, in fact I've St got it - I'll show it to you soon - lock and a key and it used to be put in there and every little so often you'd count how much you'd got. Ten - ten shillings was quite a lot those days you see. 'Cos when my f
ather got married first he hadn't had - he had fifteen shillings a week - to live on. And the other labourers, they had twelve shillings a week. You see, he was groom and gardener so he had a little more. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 So he didn't belong to any sick club or boot club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
He used to - yes, he - he was a sick club - called the Druids those days, and you I forget how much he used to pay a month, and if he was ill or anything you could get a little out - and then latterly - he used - we used to pay in for nurse 
- nurse and the - hospital. We used to pay three ha'pence a week for the nurse, threeha'pence a week for the hospital. If you had to go to hospital you had six weeks free - in the hospital. Yes. I - otherwise you - you had to pay it you see, right down - 
w
ell, people avoided going to hospital those days didn't they if they could. Yes. But now you get - done in a - quite a different way you see. And the doctors club too just the same you see. We used to pay twelve shillings, if you - you know, we didn't wor
r
y him unnecessary but - if we want him he'd come you see. For that twelve shillings a year, that's how we used to work it out. Yes. It was quite - you know - some people didn't pay and then they used to get cross because they used to - have to pay so much
, well why - why didn't you have to pay? Well, I said, I'm in this club.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 So he was really saving in several ways wasn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes, he was, yes. Yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 I don't think I asked which room exactly you had your meals in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh in - in a - 
one room, we only had the one room. We didn't have it in the little kitchen, not - not like the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 The little room was the back kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes, about the size of that. Yes. Yes, we used to always have it in front in this room, yes. YES? Always in there, mm, always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you have different food on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Well, mostly it was meat pudding that's all - mother used to have was meat pudding. And then during the week was just oddments you see, used to be mostly rabbits or any - and - now and th
en you see Mr Sharpley came out with the bloater. We had - specially harvest time he came out with the \{ILLEIGIBLE\} in the fields, yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did your mother make pickles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh yes. She did make pickles. You know - do you nasturtiums - what call n
asturtiums? Well - when I was a child we used to grow a lot of this nasturtiums we used to - when they got to the seed we used to have to pick them, and put them - mother used to put 'em in the jar and put - put the vinegar over. Well nowadays they call '
e
m capers. See? But we used to do them ourselves years ago. 'Cos they - take better that were better now to that was then, but still they used to be nice, they used to be hot. Red cabbage too they used to grow a lot of red cabbage. Used to pickle that, and
 
pickled onions. But my mother was never much to make mixed pickle, we liked - my father liked the - onions, and the capers - what - well - nasturtiums they were really. Tell you too what he used to like a lot teatime when he came in from work, the baked o
n
ions, in the oven. You see, onions with his bread. Yes. Mm. They used to be nice baked in the skins you know. Used to put a lump of butter in the - well I say lumps of butter - margarine in the middle, and - they used to thoroughly enjoy those baked onion
s. They used to get sort of a meal out of something - you know, nowadays they wouldn't look at a baked onion would they.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did your mother expect you to try to eat a bit of everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes. Yes, she did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You couldn't choose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, the
re was no choice at all, no, you had to eat what was put in front of you. Yes, used to have to eat what was put in front, else you had to go without.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Were you allowed to bring toys to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh no. No. No. They all had to be put away. They h
ad to be put away before you had a meal. Well we didn't have many toys those days. No. No. We didn't have no - just have a doll and I used to sit by the fire in a little chair - well not - the wax doll I couldn't sit by the fire with that, but I had anoth
e
r little doll, sort of a rag doll I used to nurse. Yes. I did. That was about - and then I - tell you I had - dominoes and draughts. And they were 'course Sundays we never had a - they was never allowed out on the Sunday. No. Never allowed out at all. Tho
se days were very strict. Different to now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You think your parents were very strict then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Well all - they were - all the - people were, you know, not alone mine but - all the others was just the same with children, if they dared do a thing - on a
 Sunday, no. Just used to go to church, and just sit there you know. And when you came home you just have to sit. We did used to look at a - a - a book, we' look at a book and it used to have to be - christian book, you know, not - anything else, no.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
What sort of a person would you think that your parents hoped you would grow up to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What they wanted me to grow up to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Well they didn't know quite what I was - did want, the schoolmaster wanted me to a schoolteacher. But - it d
idn't appeal to me, I suppose it's because I was an only child that a lot of children didn't sort of appeal to me. But in the end of course I went to service. Mm. And that was a drudgery I can tell you. Those days. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What did they think was most im
portant about life, were there some things they emphasised especially in bringing you up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Well you had to tell the truth for one thing. You had to tell the truth for one thing. And you had to do things just so you see. Mm. You never - oh if you told a f}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10355869\charrsid14840390 id}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390  that was so dreadful. As I found out, I know I had a hiding once ove}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10355869\charrsid14840390 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390  that. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Could you say how you think they expected you to behave towards them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh you had to look up on them as if - they was - oh up above you daren't answer them back
 at all. No, no, they - their word was their word see, you did - and you - you daren't answer them back if you did it was dreadful you know to be ; an - to answer the mother and father back, oh yes, it was. Yes, you had to behave very well those days. Yes
. you couldn't do anything unless you asked them, see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Were you allowed to talk when grown ups were talking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, no, you had to be silent. Silent, you didn't have to talk at all, no - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you find your mother was an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
She was really, but she was a - a person that was - I - she was never sort of a well - woman, see, and - 'cos she died when she was fifty, she - she always had all these - blood pressure I suppose you'd call it, blood pre - pressure, she always ha
d that, so I had to be very silent, see. And I remember I had a - concertina given me, well - I would - I daren't play that inside, always had to go right down the garden to play it. 'Course I didn't know the tunes and it used to make a row then. Yes. It 
did.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Was your father easier to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh yes, he was far easier than me mother, yes, he was. I think girls always are with the father don't you. 'Course - my mother always blamed me for not being a boy. That's the funny part, I was - you see, 
she lost the other boy, well she blamed me - 'cos I wasn't a boy, and - and of course when she - I had to come home from service to her 'cos she was - that was quite a different opinion then. 'Cos I was a girl and helped looked after her you see. But she 
- she used to say, oh girl's always a lot of bother, what with their hair and one thing and another, always a lot of bother, she said. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
So you were upset about something you would go and talk to your father would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 I - yes, I'd go to me father than me mother. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Would you say that you got your ideas about how to behave from one rather than the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, they was both the same with that, behaving, yes, they was both the same. My father was just as strict with me to behave as what me mother was. Yes. Yes he was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Do you know what they thought about swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh dear, no, I never heard such a thing. No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 They wouldn't have liked it anyway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No, he never said a word in front of me, whether he did outs
ide or not I don't know, but I don't think he did, he was one of them people - I never did hear say anything. No. No. Or me mother either. No. No. But as for children of today, well there. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Apart from this concertina, that was the only musica
l instrument in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, that was the only musical thing, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You never had a sing song?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. Well - when my father went out - he would always sing Two Little Girls in Blue. But - wherever he went, to these harvest sup - suppers, or
 - if anybody come in and - extra special and they'd say, Bill, sing us your song and then - always Two Little Girls in Blue. Always. He never knew anything else, but he'd always sing that. Mm. Yes. Mm hm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You told me about him playing draughts with 
you, did they play any other games with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, they didn't play no other games. It was only me father that played with me, me mother never did. No. Mother was nobody for that, no. No, she wasn't, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did either of them read aloud to you or to each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No. No. My father mostly - dropped - if he didn't play with me he used to drop off to sleep, they used to get so tired those days didn't they. Mm. My mother used to do this needlework at night you see, and - so therefore I was kept on
 at - as I say I'd take the tackings out of the - shirts and that but - they didn't read aloud, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Were there books in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Not very many we didn't have, no. Not like - like the children of today, what I won at school. See, what I won at 
school, for the - come - how many attendance we had and same as the - Sunday school was the same, we had these christian books you see all about the bible. And - I used to have to read those what I won, that's all the books I had. No - no pictures books l
i
ke they have of today, same as - Kit - not Tit Bits, what was the name - what's the name of the childrens - yes, you know - little - what - Tiny Tots and all like - and all like that, we never had any of them, no. No. No, no we didn't, no. No, that was a 
thing that - passed. Well, I say, thing of the past, they was never had not then, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you have any newspapers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes, my father did have a newspaper. Now - he always took - one book called John Bull. John Bull and he'd have the News of the 
World, and now what was the - daily paper? It was a Conservative paper I know. What was it called - News Chronicle - was it. No. I don't know. It's a day - daily - the Mail, no. Yes, but it was another name before Daily Mail, I can't think of that. And I 
k
now - and the man used to come round on the bicycle, he used to bike from Bardfield found with his - with the papers, but he did have a paper every day. Can't think what that was called. I know he used to take John Bull. Every week. And News of the World 
Sundays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 There was a Daily Chronicle but that was Liberal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. No, it used to be a Conservative paper, he was always dead Conservative. Forget what it was called. I don't know, I can't think. May come across to - you know think about it - can't think what it was now. No
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Any magazines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, mother never took a magazine, no, she never took a magazine. No. No she didn't take no magazines. Used to be the - church - she didn't take that even, not the church magazine. No. No, she was nobody much for - for that kind of - now I take a magazine.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 There weren't so many then I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No. No. 'Course the money you see, you had to look at all the money didn't you. Yes, you did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you feel your parents had a struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh yes, very often they did, yes. Then of course you see, there's the Pearl Insurance too, they used to pay the - so much a week for that. For in case they died you see. There was - so much a week had to go for that. And - policies, death po
licies they used to be called, always used to have to pay about a penny or three ha'pence a week, tuppence a week, mm, for that, and then when they - die you see there was that to - fall on to be buried with.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Do you remember a funeral in the family at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh yes, I remember my grandfather. I remember my grandfather - in fact - he cut his throat tell you the truth. Not cut his throat - he - drowned himself. He drowned himself in a lake, in a - lake somewhere at - Blackmore End. He was out o
f work you see and he used to go to the pubs and - he'd always like his pint of beer, and he said, I shall always have enough money, he said, to buy a pint of beer. Well he was out of work so long - children those days had to keep their parents see, not l
i
ke they do now, they used to have to find - and my mother used to send me up with food you see for them, and used to have to walk all that way with food. Well then this day - came that he drowned himself, and - my mother of course was ever so upset with t
h
at, and do you know, he'd got just tuppence ha'penny in his pocket for his beer, when they found him. Yes. Always remember that, my mother was very upset over that. Mm. Yes, you see, they used to - those out of work, they said they was lazy and all the re
st of it but it was just because they hadn't got the work to do you see. No. No. I always remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Do you remember the funeral then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, never went to it, mother wouldn't take me to it you see, she wouldn't take me to it, no, she - she went
, but - I didn't go - it was dreadful thing you see to happen like that. Yes. And there was to - I remember there was a - a man at Shalford, that was the man I was thinking about, he did cut his throat. Oh and I remember the - us children talking about it
 
you know. It was - dreadful mess, it - oh dear, and he cut his throat just through taking a - packet of those - matches I think. And he cut his throat. And I said, oh he shouldn't be buried in churchyard and all the rest of it. Oh there was such a to do a
b
out that you know but in the end he was, he was - the first one to be buried on a - new bit of ground at Shalford church. Yes. Yes. So as - as children at school there no sex or anything like there is nowadays. No, I mean us children didn't know anything 
w
hatever until we - left school and - had our periods and then our mothers'd just tell us, but then she didn't tell us the result, just said that - you know, we'd have our periods each month. But not - what it was for or anything. You just had to find that
 our yourself and that was four - I was fourteen or fifteen before I knew anything about that. Mm. See now today they teach 'em a school everything don't they. Great different year - that was very sacred that was years ago, very sacred that bit.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did children not talk about that sort of thing themselves though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, not at school, no. No, never said a word. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 A big change from the schools now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. Not a word they didn't say, not a word. And of course my mother asked me she said, haven
't you had - anybody else say anything? I said, no I haven't much She said, what not so and so, 'cos, she said, her mother told me that so and so happened. I said, no she didn't. Well she said, she's a very good girl not to tell you. But today they know h
ere before they go to school really don't they. It's quite the - the reverse you see. Mm. Yes, quite the reverse. I can always remember that. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Do you remember going on any outings with your parents on Bank Holidays?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. We never had no out
ings at all - when it was - holiday we had to work and - do all jobs in the - what wanted doing, I used to - my mother used to paper the room and - and that and we used to have to - I used to have to help - do all that See, or help scrub a floor for her, 
I used to get the water for her or anything. Because we used to - cart the water, there was noting laid on you see. No. All jobs like that had to be done on holidays. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You didn't ever go away for a holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No. No. Never went away for a h
oliday at all. No. And I haven't been since I've been married. No I haven't. No. Not a holiday I haven't had away from home. Only when I've been in to hospital. I call that my holiday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You must work hard all the time then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did they ever take you out to visit friends or neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh yes, you go out as - same as these friendship - clubs of today you go out visiting, you - go to seasides and that, but - I never went in a train 'til I was eighteen. Never went in a train 'til I was eighteen. And that's when I used to go up to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} every day with the families when I was in service you see. Yes
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 But before you started work you would go out visiting with your parents?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh yes, she'd take me to see my grandmother or my - b
ut we had to walk. Had to walk wherever we were had to walk, we couldn't go nowhere - unless you walked. Mm hm. Or you - had to hire but - a horse and trap from Shalford George, but - we didn't go far 'cos all our relations lived round you see, so we had 
- we just walked you see. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 There was your grandmother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes, she lived at Blackmore End. And my grandmother at Shalford - she lived at Shalford you see. Se we used to have to walk one place and walk the other. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What other relations would you see besides the grandmothers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Well they used to - come home you see to - well they used to work near you see, they didn't work far away at the farms you see, they go into service, and that and be the - two of them that are - servants at the fa
rmhouse you see, and my aunt used to come home and I used to visit - well she used to come to our house you see, like that, yes, we never - went - far away from Shalford or - Blackmore End. No. And - and then - only when we walked to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Braintree{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} to go shopping. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did your parents have other friends besides relatives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes - a Fleshman from up here, he was a friend of my father's. And - then there' be - you see, they used to go and meet at Shalford George you see when he used to drink so they use
d to go and meet each other there but - didn't very often have people in the house like they do today. No. I suppose you see they couldn't feed them, they hadn't got enough food and therefore they didn't come you see. They used to come perhaps and walk ro
und the garden, see the gardens but - not to come in the - house visiting much, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 They wouldn't come in without being invited?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh no. No. Got to be invited if they did come, yes, they did, yes. Yes.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 If they did come in they would be given some food would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh yes. Always homemade wine. Homemade wine. That was always a treat. Homemade - oh if - if you come in - if they come to - be in the garden, oh you must come in and try a glass of my wife's home made wine you see, that was alw
ays home made then. Rhubarb used to be the most what they used to make. Yes. Rhubarb wine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 And they'd just sit and talk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Just sit and talk, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 And your father might sing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, that's right, yes. Yes. Yes, Christmas time or birt
hday times, yes. But otherwise there was nothing - much you see, it all seemed to be work, was always busy. Mm. Yes, or they were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
When your parents had friends or relatives in apart from occasionally singing and talking did they play any games or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No. No, they wouldn't play a game, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No other ways of making their own amusement?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. Yes, you see they used to go down to the George you see and that, and had amusements down there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 More amusing than at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did your mother ever go out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, she didn't go far, no, not my mother, no. No. My uncle, he had one of those very old fashioned - gramaphones, with a - have you see them with - not - not the - no, did have a big horn but - very ol
d ones oh with a ring, you slip 'em on same as like you would slide anything on there. That was very old. Well they used to have them to play those days. And - but we never had one but my uncle did, yes. He had one and - they used to go and listen to it, 
to his house sometimes, yes. And - but we never had a - any music of any type - anything at all - not at home, no. My mother was - always got this headache you see, well - to be quiet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did she not have really any interests outside the house?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Not
 a lot, no. No, she didn't, no. No. I tell you if she knew of anybody having a - baby she would make these - shoe - socks, yes. You've heard that before but - otherwise she - didn't have a lot, no, she was all - she was - she used to work at the mill you 
s
ee, well she was all day, she'd take perhaps a lot - an hour nearly to dust a chair like that. See? It - it's marvelous really what you do now to what she did then, she was so slow you see. Mmm. So slow in doing her work. I think you are - and she - when 
she married first she didn't know anything much, she had to learn off the next door neighbour. Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 That was because she'd been working before you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 She'd been working in the mill. At {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Braintree{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, well - she was not home, she - not ho
me much you see off - to learn off of her mother. No, she used to learn - cooking and - sewing and all sorts off the next door neighbour. Mm. I've heard her say so anyway. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 If she was ill who would help her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Well I used to have to do all - th
e necessary work you see really and then she'd got my - grandmother. My father's mother used to help her you see, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Not a neighbour in that case?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, no, we - they was oldish neighbours that we had, yes. Very old - next door up - to Hill Farm, that they couldn't do anything much for her, no. No they didn't, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Would you say that your mother and father had different friends or that they shared their friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh they'd share the friends together you know, anybody come and that, m
other always made 'em welcome, and so did my father. - He always made - if mother did ask anybody, which was very rare, she all - they always made 'em well - but whichever - and it was - they was always welcome. Mm. Yes. She - they wouldn't be nasty with 
each other, no. No, they'd always be welcome. Mm. Yes. They would. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You were saying that your father was as Conservative?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh - rosettes, the rosettes, rosettes. Oh dear. And he'd go mad over it. Another house up here, well Sir Fortesque Flynn, he was - came and lived there, he went into Parliament. They get him on - when he got in Parliament - he - from Shalford to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Wethersfield{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - cor - they used to get him on their shoulders and they used to carry him along the road, get him out of his car, car
ry him along the road. Oh dear, and he'd come home - I've been to the manor he said, and mother said, yes, I know you have. She said, and what do you feel like now? He'd roll about like this. He'd been down at the George, he'd had this beer and that. Oh i
t
 was a do that was, and then - and - voting time they'd go nearly mad, why I don't know but he would. And all us children even we had to have the rosettes on, the blue rosettes, just the same as the - mothers and fathers, we had to - although we didn't kn
ow what it was really for, but we had to wear them the same.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 And your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. Yes. The same. Yes. Oh dear, that - I mean now it's not so exciting those - voting days there was then. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Do you know why he was a Conservative?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Don'
t know at all, just - well years ago they always used to think - church people was Conservative, chapel people was Liberal, see, they always went like that. So you - used to know which was which.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You don't think it mattered which way your employer voted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No. That didn't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Didn't people have to follow their employers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No. No. 'Cos mostly you see they were church goers who - who - Conservatives, but they didn't - the chapel people - there's not many chapel people at Shalford, not
 those days, no. No. No. My father always used to laugh on Easter Sunday. There was just one or two used to bike past to come up here to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Wethersfield{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 chapel and he'd say, here, there's the fair today. Just - just to see what the chapel people had got new o
n you see. Always had to have something new for Easter - chapel people did, and - he said, there's - there's Wetherfield fair coming now, he says, you look at the new clothes they've got on today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 He didn't think much of the chapel people then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No, he didn't think much of chapel. And yet I - I married - my husband is chapel and I'm church. Isn't that funny? - Mm. But that doesn't count, we never - you know - we never discuss it or anything, he does his way and I - I go where I - like, he goe
s where he likes, in fact he doesn't go anywhere much. But I do go to church every Sunday evening but now there's no church on Sunday evening. 'Til we get a new vicar and then we'll - see shall have it again. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Going back to that time do you think th
ere was a difference between the church and chapel people?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh yes, there was. Yes there was. Yes. Yes - they - I don't know, there was - just that difference you could - I don't know what - how I could describe that, but - they didn't seem so - as -
 they seemed to be more deceitful if I can - if you can make it out. Chapel people's more deceitful than the church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You mean they said they believed in things which they didn't really do?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes. That's right, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What sort of things do you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Well - they was always fining fault of each other and all like that, but you never heard a church person do that, see. That kind of thing. Yes. Oh so and so and so and so, you know, and - or - I don't believe in her, I don't believe in her
 and all like that but you didn't hear a church people say that. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What sort of jobs did the chapel people have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh they done the same kind of jobs, oh yes, they worked with the church people, oh yes, they used to work with the church people a
nd that, yes, just the same. Mm. But it was just that little bit of difference you see, yes. Yes. I don't know why it was, I don't know at all, but I just remember that. Mm. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did your mother take any interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Not a lot, 'co
s - because she used to get fed up with them, the - she used to say, oh is there another election, have I got to go through it again? Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Your father didn't actually belong to some political club or party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No, he's none - none of - no, not 
like that then, no. No. Just this voting you see, of course the women didn't vote those days did they, it was only the - the men that voted you see, that was all. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Would he canvass for people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, there's no canvassing like that those days, 
no. No. Do I - if it was I didn't - know about it. No. No. 'Course the elections used to go on perhaps several years in between those days to what it is now doesn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You mean it went on for a long time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes. Yes. Yes. And each time of co
urse a Conservative man got in you see. Used to be Sir Fortesque Flynn who got in well - I went to serve there after a while. Mm. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Before your father gave up drinking how many times a week would your father normally go out to the pub?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Well 
he used to go out - I should - how many nights a week he'd go, I suppose he used to go about three times a week, and then he used to - have his beer at home as well you see, yes. Harvest time always beer at home, but - there's no other time - beer at home
,
 no. Mm. He wasn't a heavy drinker, not what you call a heavy drinker, but he did like his drop of beer. Yes. And of course they used to treat each other down there and - and see if they could get somebody tipsy you see and that was their delight, that wa
s their play.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You never were allowed to go up there yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No. No. Never allowed you in a public house. No. No. They thought it was dreadful if a - you know, the church people were - publican, oh he never went to church you see, well he co
uldn't because he'd got his - pub opened you see, but there you are, they thought that was awful 'cos he couldn't go to church. Mm. Mm. They used to like him though, he used to be known - But - Bucher. Mm, Butcher up at - George. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You mentioned your father's interest in going on the hunt?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh yes. Yes, he used to love to go hunting. In fact I've got a - picture somewhere now outside the Dog Inn up there where he was on a horse with his hat - hat they used to have, hard hats there, and - he use
d to go when Mr Ling couldn't go you see, he used to go with Mrs Ling. Yes. Used to love horses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did he go to the races at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No. There was no - I don't think there was races was there then? No, not near - they wasn't no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Newmarket?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes, no, he never went there, no. No. Only thing I can remember horses is that - when they used to come to the fairs you see, used to be - lot of 'em them come and then - as I tell you, they was cruel those old stirrups with the wheels on them. To mak
e the poor horses bleed you know, make round a ring - dance, yes. Mm. But they were more - they talk about cruel nowadays but they was more cruel I think years ago to animals than they are today some of - I know some of 'em put the dogs and that on these 
c
hains and that but - years ago you could see 'em slash 'em you know with the whips and that but you don't see 'em so much nowadays. No. They used to kick the poor horses in the stomach and that you know. But - and the pigs, the same you see, they used to 
h
ave these big thick sticks and slash 'em if they didn't go just where they wanted 'em and the goats the same. Yes. 'Cos they used to be on roads you see more ago - years ago, never used to be carted from one place to the other, used to have to walk, poor 
animals did. Sheep. Rowas and rows of sheep. Mm. Yes. Rows and rows of sheep. And take them from one field to another you see, perhaps from one village to another, wherever there's feed for them. Yes. Poor things. Mm. Miles.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Would be interested in cricket?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No. No cricket those days. Not at Shalford. There was no cricket, but there used to be up here at Wetherfield. But there's nothing at Shalford, they had no cricket field or anything there, no. No, a very - village for no - cricket and that, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No football?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No. No football, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No other sports?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No. No. Not at Shalford there wasn't. No. Don't remember as a child. No.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What about yourself, you don't remember taking any part in sports as a child?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, only
 at these - we used to have the maypole. We used to have a maypole, we used to have to do that at twenty - fourth of May wasn't it. Used to have the maypole. Used to - be on, used to - the mothers and fathers used to see us do the maypole, we used to do t
h
at. And - that was - good really, the maypole was. Yes, and - that's about all I can remember we used to do for - twenty-fourth of May. Mm. But - then we used to have to do it in the school grounds because there's no where else to do it, there's no playin
g fields or anything for them. We used to play on the roads you see. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What sort of games did you play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Well marbles you see, used to be marbles first and then tops. And then there used to be skipping ropes and hoops - these old farm hoops, and
 - then rounders, with a ball, you know, game of rounders. And - but there was no ten - there used to be I think the gentry used to play tennis - and hockey, they used to play more up at the manor, I've seen 'em when I've been up to my grandmother's. Play
 hockey, but - there was nothing else for the poor, no. Not at Shalford, not those days, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Who would you play with as a child?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh well we used to have our own little friends. Yes. We used to have our little group of friends, I - still hear fro
m my - one. We used to go - go to each other's houses and play you see. Us two was - an only child, her name was Eva Grubb, and she married a hairdresser in a row at Kelvedon his name - there they got it but - we still hear every birthday and every Christ
m
as, we still have our cards. Yes, we got we used to go to their house - and mothers used to say, now you be here at certain time, if you're not I shall worry, and - of course it - and I used to be - come back and - we used to go backwards and forwards you
 
see us two together. Mm hm. But she used to live at the Lodge, that was all, and I used to live at Hill Farm, that's the nearest we had of - children, yes. Yes, nearest children we had, but we always used to - we - always used to go to each other's houses
 us two did and - of course the mother and fathers would - they were friends together you see, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 So that's how you met her really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. Yes. Yes. She was my age you see and - even to this day - every birthday she always writes me a card and I 
do her and the same at Christmas just the same. Yes. We've kept it up all those years from the time I was - went out to service until even now. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 There was no one else you played with then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, no, not - no, I mean I would ask me mother 
if I could go and then - if you do you be home by a certain time, but she didn't - she wouldn't let me out far, not my mother wouldn't - no. I was an only child and I said if ever we got married I'd never have - been - have an only child if I could help i
t. So I had two daughters you see. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Was there anyone that she discouraged you from playing with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh yes, specially a girl with - had - had lice in her hair. Used to - there's one poor girl, you couldn't blame the child, because she lived with 
her grandmother. And the grandmother couldn't see very well, but that child was lousy, her hair. And I can see it now you know to this day and - if I went anywhere near her of course I know I should get something in it and that and mother said, you've bee
n near that girl again. Oh mum, I said, you can't help it at school, you - you can't help it. And of course I had all this thick hair and didn't I used to have to go through it at night. With a little tiny comb and that you know. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Was she shunned by the other children at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
She was a bit, yes, she was, but I felt very sorry for her. I did really, because - she was a nice girl and she couldn't help it, she couldn't do it herself. She lived with her granny. Mm. 'Cos her mother had her you see and \{ILLEGIBLE\} }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10355869\charrsid14840390 Otherwise I}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Were there any sort of clubs that you could belong to as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No. Was no clubs. No, no clubs at all. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You said you kept a rabbit, did you have any other pets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 A cat. A cat, that was all I had, a cat and a rabbit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you collect anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Not really. No. Flowers, we used to go primrose day we used to go round and - collect primroses. And - see how many we could get.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You had a ha'penny a week then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Ha'penny a week, yes, ha'penny a week, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you help your father in the garden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh yes, I did, I used to help him in the garden. Think I did tell you the tale about the bull didn't I? Well he - he - he told me what to do you see 'cos he - couldn't get on his le
g, and they used to - go round with this little fork and - go all the way round the borders and all that and do that, but that was - that was a bit then he had, when he couldn't finish his garden real off you know, but anyway he had first prize for it. Ye
s
. Yes. He did have first prize. And - when the bull - when they said - saw - that was the bull - poor old Will Condor they said had a bull in his garden today. Oh dear, it wasn't - and of course it was the man's name. So I suppose a laugh over that in the
 village down the George over that. Mm. Mm hm. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You didn't go fishing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes, he - well he didn't exactly fish in - but he used to put a snare, he lived near the river you see, well worked near the river, and he used to put a snare. And he used
 to bring home the loveliest trout sometimes he'd catch in this name. My mother used to do it in the oven in the vinegar, and - it used to be lovely really it was, yes. And even the - the milk, I never told you - our milk was always boiled in the oven. Si
d
e of the oven. And it used to be lovely this skimmed milk was. And I always had the top off of it when it come - used to be brown when it come out the oven. 'Cos it - when it keeps boiling and boiling it goes like this carnation milk does you know what yo
u
 buy of today, it used to be real good too. Yes. Lots of things was done in the oven those days which are not done now. No. Yes, skimmed milk always 'cos you see you had to boil it as soon as you got it, this skimmed milk. Used to be jolly nice it did too
.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 As a child would you ever have gone to a concert?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Well we used to have to do it - as children ourselves you see. The schoolmaster used to get up this concert - and - then the mothers and fathers used to go you see and it - I don't know what th
e money went for, what they used to have to pay to go in. Or if it was just - I can't remember that, whether the mothers and fathers were just invited, was at the school. We used to have to say recitations and do little plays and then sing you know. That 
was an evening that we used to be weeks practicing. Yes. but today the children don't do it do they. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Were you taken to any concerts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No. Only what we done ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Theatre?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 When did you first go to the cinema?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh - when I was in London that was the year, you know, when I was in service, when I used to go up and down, yes. No, there was no - I - I remember the Embassy being built in Braintree and that was - oh, after I was - grown up then that was. Th
ere was no - no - no pictures or anything, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 So the fair was really the only entertainment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Interest, yes, only interest that used to be in this meadow here one year, and then I tell you at Shalford another year. Yes. That was our enjoyment, a fair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What did they have there besides the horses in the ring?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Well the swing boat - swinging boats. Swimming boats and - coconut shies. What else was there? And of course you could buy the rock, you could see 'em make this rock you see, you co
uld see them make it. Used to be nice rock, brown rock. Thick lumps. What did they have there. Oh of course they had a stall with all sorts of things on you could buy you see. I don't know if I've got anything here now, no, that I had from there. Used to 
buy all the stuff, used to have all sorts of things there, beads and - dollies and - candlesticks and - haven't got anything here, no. Same as all little ornaments like that they'd have, yes. But - that's all they had at the fairs then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Any other performers besides the animals?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No, only - no, not - there's not much performing of animals those days really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 But were there clowns?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh yes, walking on stilts. Yes, there was clowns walking on the stilts. Yes. And we used to think that was great fun to see him with his big nose. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What about nigger minstrels?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No, never saw any of those. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 They didn't have any actors?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No. No. It used to be included you see with the flower show as well. You see, the flower show used to be at the same time as - and the fair used to come at the same time, that used to be a big day that day. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you have a ploughing match for instance, anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, I don't think they did. They used to have stackin
g. The best stack. The best - built stack. Might have had a ploughing match, but I know they did stack. How it was thatched, you know, thatched. A bill used to go in, whoever thatched it used to go but I think my - one of my uncles used to do thatching - 
m
y father build the stack, all round the sides and the old man could do the middle but my father done round the sides. My uncle used to thatch, he used to have prizes for the - best stack. Mm. But I - I think it - don't think - there's anything else. Can't
 remember, might have been ploughing, but - can't remember there. I know - remember the stacks. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 They didn't have little booths, like the fat lady and that kind of thing?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No. No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 It was just really one main tent was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes, just this - yes, just the - tents of flower - show, that was all there was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 A tent for the flower show?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 And another one for the animals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 For - animals, yes. Yes. Yes. All the flower - flowers and - sweet peas an 
\{ILLEGIBLE\}
 stand like that and down, it used to be about a - all the vegetables you could have, what they called a collection of vegetables for the flower show. And there used to be the best rose, and that had to be on velvet. My father used to do a - velvet box
, and there used to be a rose stuck in you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Were there speeches at the beginning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. Yes. Yes, you know these - that kind of thing, then the best - best - flower - used to have prizes for the best - window with flowers in. That's why I al
ways like my flowers. Always remember my mother's flowers in the window. She always used to do 'em - a lot - water them with cold tea. If ever you knew anything like it, but always cold tea, all her flowers was watered with cold tea. And - I've heard - yo
u
 know, other people saying that - they used to do it the same, but I don't, I do it with generally water. Mm. Always cold tea. I don't know what - what - why they did it, it's - I suppose it's like a fertilizer what they use in they days isn't it. Yes, th
at's the idea of it, yes. But - I tell you there used to be the garden and the window.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Was there somebody who opened the fear?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes, there used to be the Secretary of this you see, the - Secretary of the flower show, and the head one, used to be p
erhaps Squire Marriott or a - Ling at Shalford Hall, they used to say it was open you see. Yes. Used to have to get up - used to walk from Shalford right up to here with the stuff in these big baths, and the same - when - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Wethersfield{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} people used to have to do the same when that was at Shalford you see. And they used to have their own cups and saucers with the initials on, Shalford and 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Wethersfield{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Used to have the cups of tea and that. Up there. Cakes. Eggs - used to be for - be - be all in these tents. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Would you say then that Mr Ling and Squire Marriott were the most important people in the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh they were, and the vicar. And the vicar. Oh yes. You had to look up to - the same as now - they used to be - real - what we called gentleman
, the vicar was, he was brought up high up you know but - same as nowadays now like - a poor old person's - son could be a vicar can't they, they can have education and get up you see, but them days, oh no, you see, they used - to be the - squire's son or
 the vic - or the - vicar's son you see, they was the - or the vicar I mean, they were the only ones that - you used to have to look up to them, yes. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you have to curtsey them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh yes, you had to curtsey to them. Or lift your hat. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Were you taught by your parents to do that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. Yes. Yes. Yes, was always - to do that. Yes. And it used to be amusing too. The vicar, if he got to know Squire Marriot was round visiting the poor, away he used to go, trot along too. He - y
ou see, they had pony and carts then you see. Away he'd go too - oh, somebody said, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10355869\charrsid14840390 S}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 quire Marriott is about today, away the vicar'll go too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Why did he do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
I don't know, so he should be - so he should be known that he should - he'd be about visiting you see. Yes. So show Squire Marriott you know that he was visiting, yes. Funny the ideas they used to have really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What about the shopkeepers, were they looked up to in that way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, not so much the shopkeepers, no. No, they were sor
t of working - class like the others, shopkeepers was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You wouldn't lift your hat to a shopkeeper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No. Oh no, no, only to these - others, yes. Mm. I never shall forget once - just beginning - just - at the beginning of the war, this is a tal
e this is - I was at the manor, and - the butler and that had to go to war you see, and of course we used to have a woman - looking after - Sir Fortesquis clothes. He was - you - you - you'd laugh to have seen her. She dressed up in Sir Fortesque's clothe
s
 and she came down the passage like this, I'm Sir Fortesque she said, and he came out of the toilet well I - and I never shall forget, never in my life. Oh he - I can remember that to this day. Oh - Kate, they used to call her Aunt Kate, poor Aunt bate di
d
n't know what to do, she didn't know where to put herself she come through shooting through to the kitchen. Good gracious, she said, I shall get on the carpet for this, but she didn't, he never said a word. I reckon he could see the funny side of it. Poor
 
Aunt Kate. And then as a maid too I was up there. I used to have to take the cat out - at night, last thing at night, sometimes the cat wouldn't come in, I daren't go indoors again without the cat. What I used to do - do was, we was just as bad years ago,
 
was ever so - I mean, we didn't do the mischief, I used to put a box of dirt in a - butler's pantry, then I used to shut the cat in there, make it do what it would do, and - then I used to keep walking round the house calling Bish, Bish, Bish, Bish, and t
h
at's the cat's name, I used to have to take it in me arms you see to get the fresh air into it, 'cos she used to have such a lot of scent - and so - and came in, oh - oh she's come in all right? Yes, m'lady, she's come in all right, she hadn't been outsid
e
. Cat hadn't been outside. 'Cos that used to play me up sometimes I used to - have to sit up at twelve o'clock if that cat was outside you see. So it would come in. So she - done it - but the cat done it once too often to me - for me, so I - I had that on
e on to it. That's how we used to make a bit of fun you see and - dear oh dear. Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 When you say the poor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Do you mean the ordinary working people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. Some of 'em were very poor. I mean, they only had a half a crown a week live 
on you see and that was the - widows who were left you see and - they had just a half a crown what they called poor money. Well then their - sons and daughters used to have to - keep the rest of 'em you see, pay the rent as well. Mm. They used to go round
 
the - from the farmers and Squire Marriott and they used to go round with soup and - what they could get for them, you see, soup with some nice piece of cake and that. And then built the alms houses here, my grandmother - she lived up there, she only had 
half a crown a week and Lady Flanner used to allow them a half a pint of milk a day you see. Make that - that was what we used to call the poor. Mm, but - nowadays there's not the poor like there was. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What about the Guardians, did they help them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh, well you see the - Guardians of today like is - what do you call it - National Assistance - isn't it, yes. Well the poor you see, there used to be a man come round, his name was Mr Tyder, and he used to go round and - deliver this money, half a cr
own a week to them. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 That was from the Guardians?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Your grandmother got that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. She got that half a crown a week. Yes. And a loaf of bread from the church. A loaf of bread from the church she used to have. A week. What
 they called groat money, that was left - a legacy to the church you see and the poor used to have to have this, yes. Yes. Well what would they think of today. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Your parents really were a bit better off than most working people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes, th
ey were, yes, yes. Bit better off. Yes, 'cos you see they had that little bit extra, that made all that difference you see. Yes, it did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Do you think that made them feel themselves slightly different from the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, no. No. No they weren't, no, they was no different, no. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Would you say there was any difference at that time between craftsmen and people who hadn't learned a craft?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Well - don't know if they made much difference to each other, I don't think they did, no, but I did
n't - think that they did, they was all friendly together and that, yes. There's no - sort of - in the - village, there was nobody didn't seem no higher than the others. No. No they didn't, no.1
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 But what about a family which was thought of as being rather rough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Mm. Well they was - not - very many rough people about, was one - one - poor old man, Charlie Carter, we used to call him, he - he was rough, he used to sleep rough, anywhere he'd sleep, and - he used to get - earn a penny where he could,
 see, that's only rough one I know. I remember - he used to walk backwards and forwards from Shalford to Wethersfield and if you - you wanted a little odd job done he'd do it for about a penny you see, just to get a penny. Or - or a little bit of food, if
 
you could spare him a little bit of - bread and butter, he was quite thankful for that. He never really - had a job, he was sort of rough, and yet he got brothers quite all right, they used to work and that, but he - he didn't like work. He used to sit fo
r hours, there used to be a stone up here at the Lion, he used to sit hours on that stone. Yes. Outside the Lion, well then that was made into a hospital during the war. And - sit there, do off jobs. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 He didn't have a home though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No home a
t all, no, used to go about in rags, people used to give him - anything you know, what they got - what they say they didn't want it and they used to give 'em to him, you know, an old pair of shoes they'd left off, well he'd he glad of 'em to wear, he woul
d, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 He had no wife I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, no wife at all, no, no. No. That's the only rough person that I did know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 There were no families as a whole like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, no. No. No. That was the only rough person I did know, was no - no families was - rough, they was like we were, you know, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What about gipsies, you didn't have any gipsies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Well the gipsies used to come round occasionally but - not a lot really. No. No. Used to come round and buy rabbit skins, you know, occasi
onally, rabbit skins, got rabbits skins por - pegs they used to come round with. Mm hm. And - if my mother wanted a dozen she'd buy a dozen well that would be about a penny a dozen you see. Pegs. Mm. But they used to last you see, we used to have to make 
the things last year ago. Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You thought of them as being very different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. Yes. We didn't care a lot for gipsies, no. No. No, they used to have the capes as a child here and that but - didn't care a lot for them. Thought we didn't see may o
f them, no. Not - no, well you don't - much of today really not about here, any rate, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 There are some villages where they seem to have settled in though.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, they do, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Was that true here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 They never settled round our way 
at all. Not unless it was pea picking, perhaps they - if they heard of a field being - pea picked then they'd come and - and - bring the caravan and - you know, and just pick peas and away they'd go again. Yes. Away they'd go. But there's one gipsy - 'cos
 I've just lately been down to Finchingfield and they spend no end of money on that grave for flowers every year. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Were there any other travelling people like travelling Irishmen coming for the harvest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No, not like there is - no, no
. No, they used to have about a dozen men you see on the farm and that used to be the lot, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You don't remember the people from Shalford or 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Wethersfield{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} going to other villages to help with the harvest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No. No. No, they used to have 
their own, they had to do it you see. There are here about a dozen people and they used to do it. Yes. That's the dog. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
You did say that you felt your parents had a struggle to make ends meet, did you ever - what did you feel about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Well
 they did at times more or less, that was - when it was rent time, that - that was the time - they could sell a few apples you see to - get the - help get the rent together, but then - I think my mother was very careful, and she used to put a little by wh
en she could to help with it you see. And so did my father, especially after he gave up drink, there was the money for this the money for that you see. So they didn't have to worry. No. Didn't have to worry.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Who was the landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Shalford Hall -
 Mr Ling, yes. I think I told you, three pound a year rent and find your own fireplace. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Was he a good landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, not too bad, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What if repairs were needed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, well he - no repairs really wanted, 'cos so many yea
rs ago they built a house, it - that house - if you built - anybody built a new house it had to stand six months before anybody went in it. See? Nowadays they're in it before ever it's finished building. That has to stand to dry out, for six months, befor
e anybody dare go in it. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 But yours was quite old?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes, ours was old one, it's still there now. And it - it's three houses they was - it's been made into two now. Bathrooms of course have been added to it, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you never have the roof leaking for instance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No. No. Never had - 'cos they were built those days weren't they, they weren't flung together like they are now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 The craftsmanship's different isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes. Yes. Yes there was. Mm. hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 If there was som
ebody in the district that the people disapproved of very strongly, can you remember how they'd show that, their feelings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, I don't think so. They all approved of each other really, we lived happily all - you know, all the village seemed happy together. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You never heard of rough music?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No. No. No, there's no rough music or anything, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 We found that in some villages round here that they used rough music.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You did? Yes. No. No, there was no rough music, no. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Or sending somebody to Coventry, you never came across that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No. No. No, there was nothing of that, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 I think it varies from village to village.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Village I think they had different - things didn't they, was very quiet at Shalford really, yes, very quiet. Mm. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Was there sometimes a feeling that other villages were different at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No, 'cos you see Shalfrod was very much - like 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Wethersfield{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and the other side - was just about the same, yes. Yes. Used to 
have a little hamlet in Jasper's Green and that was just the same as Shalford you know, yes, same as Blackmore End was just the same as - Shalford.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
I've sometimes heard that people say that their parents wouldn't have anything to do with people from the next village, but that's not so here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No. Not round about this way, no. Oh dear no. No. No, they was all friendly together, yes. Mm hm. No, I never heard that, no. No. And the children, they was all friendly, I don't say that they would - they
 didn't know 'em, they'd say just hullo and pass 'em by mind but they wouldn't - wouldn't be unfriendly. No. No. Not unfriendly, no. No, always used to live all in harmony. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Before you went to school did your parents teach you anything like your
 letters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh yes. I think I knitted before I went to school, I think my mother learnt me to knit before I went to school. And to sew too. Yes. I always used to have to sit - she used to make these shirts, and I used to have to sit and turn the - sewi
ng machine for her. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 She didn't teach you to read or something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, I don't - no. I don't remember her teaching me to read. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 How old were you when you started school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh I suppose I was about - five, think on five I suppose, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 And that was at Shalford?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Shalford school, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 The church school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 School, yes, there was another school, only the - church school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Boys and girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, boys and girls together, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 How many teachers were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Three. The headmaster, and then - he was - forget what standards it was now, seven, six and five I think, and then there was the teacher for the - four - and the threes, and then there was the - infant teacher for the ones and twos. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What were the teachers like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh very nice really, one schoolmaster we had was a \endash 
 pass on he was, he'd cane the boys and that but - always they were - we had - the last schoolmaster I had at school was name Hiscock, he's dead now, but - he got c
hildren of his own and he understood children more, see. I think you do when you - you've - got children. And the other - two schoolmasters we had had got no children, and they were more stricter you know, yes, they were. More stricter. But - the last sch
oolmaster, Hiscock, he was very good. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 He rather changed the atmosphere?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. Yes. Because - I'll tell you another thing we used to do, you see, he'd got children well we made - we made such a fuss 'cos he'd got these children, he'd got two gi
rls and a boy, we made such a fuss and he - he had us up one day, now look children, he said, you're to - not to make no more fuss of my children than - any others, he said, they're to be treated just as you're treated, see. Mm. And if they wanted the sti
ck he used to give them the stick the same as he he would anybody else, yes. If they were - didn't behave in school. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Was that true of the other teachers though - that they would treat all the children the same way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes. Yes. Yes, that w
as the motto of that school. Yes. Got to treat all alike you know. Anybody misbehaved, well they had to be punished or - stand up in the corner and not move you know. And - or write so many words. Mostly it was stand up in the corner. Face the corner and 
daren't move. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you like it at school or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
I didn't mind at school, no. I didn't mind it at all. I used to get on well really at school. Mm. I know they was ever so pleased if the schoolmaster asked them a - asked us anything, we used t
o put up our hands like this if we knew the answer you see, if you didn't know the answer \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 kept down. I always remember one question he asked - why do people go - to the sea in the daytime? Why was it - well - I thought, that isn't only what - I
 know, it's - I said, I well it's cooler - the sea breezes - I said - in the day time, but at night - land the sea breezes go. Yes, quite right. That's the only question I can remember. Oh and a candle. Why do candles burn? Well, said, because they draw u
p - the - wax and it keeps them alight. I do remember those two questions, I put up my hand ever so quickly for that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did they emphasise tidiness, manners and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh yes, at school, oh yes, we used to have to sit still and that and
 - and - we didn't have to blot our papers you know and - used to ink - pen, you know, we use to have dip our pens in ink different to what they do now. If you had a blot on the paper, oh - get a tap on the hand for that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What about if you were late at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh - we had to give a - why it was we was late, didn't we get up early enough an all the rest of it and - his - children was late one day at school, he'd go on to them the same. Of course he knew, he knew why they was late, but - he got on 
to them just the same as he would us - you see, yes. Mm mm. Yes, it's - you know it was - very strict at school those days they were. Mm. Daren't speak to the one next door, if you - if you did - or copied anybody's - oh my word, was in for it then, if yo
u just looked over like that and - to copy if you didn't know the answer and tried to see the other person. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did your parents ever go up to the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
At - in the evenings when we used to have - same as the concerts and that and - but they d
idn't go up like they do today, only they just started - as I left - was beginning to leave school they just started the doctors coming around and having a look, you know, inspections, to you - for your teeth and that, yes. Just started that and - 'course
 the parents was - didn't like that at all really. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Why not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
I don't know why, they thought that - don't know why they didn't like it, but didn't like that at all. Mm. But I will say my mother always kept me clean and tidy you know and nice an
d that underneath. She said, you'll have underneath clothes if you don't have outside clothes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Ash Wednesdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
We had to have a piece of ash - Ash Wednesday. Didn't I? Oh we had to have a piece of ash, my father used to cut a - me a piece o
f ash - out of the hedge, it must be ash, 'cos it's Ash Wednesday. If you haven't got a piece of ash in your pocket - you used to be nipped - by whoever found you without a piece of ash. Oh used to - oh they did used to pinch you hard too. So we - made su
re we had a piece of ash. This was Ash Wednesday. Haven't you heard that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Going back to the school, did your parents take an interest in what you were doing at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh yes, yes, they used to - I used to have a slate at home you see and I used
 to - often do - ask them to - ask my father to give me a sum to do you see. We didn't have no homework, but I say dad - something to do, I used to ask him to - have a sum see if I could get it right you see, yes. Slate lasted us for years. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 How long were you at this school then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
I went a little longer than others because - tell you for why, the sex problem, mother didn't want me to go out anywhere until that - that was all over with, and I went 'til I was fourteen. Yes. But some of the other
 children left at thirteen you see and had to go out to work. They used to go out to work there are scrub floors, do all these fireplaces and all sorts at their age. Yes. They did. Thirteen. But I was lucky really, I didn't go 'til I was fourteen. Mm.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 They wanted you to be a teacher at one point?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Well, they didn't but the schoolmaster did. The schoolmaster did. But - it didn't appeal to me somehow. Then after year - after I'd been in service I wished I had have done. 'Cos it was much harder in service than being a school teacher. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 So you went into service immediately after leaving school did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. No. I went as day girl. Day girl first, a half a crown a week. Half a crown a week I had, I used to - go in the morning about - seven and come home again just at dark you see. Half a crown a week, seven days a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Where was that for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Down at Hulls at Shalford. She used to be an actress, she used to come down there, and she had this cottage - down there, well then I left there - and then I went - she gave up the house and then I went in -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Could you tell me a little bit more about her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh actress, oh she used to come down weekends and sometimes used to stay in the week, her name was Mrs Bruce Smith, she was. And then
 there used to be - a friend used to come, I think she was getting divorced from her husband, his name was Bill Crompton. A funny thing. And - then they gave up the house, they - they got a London house, they lived at Maida Vale. They gave this little cot
tage up and went back to London. But -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Were you a maid there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes, I had to have stiff collars, stiff collars and a black frock and in the morning a blue - frock with these big aprons on. Well all that pocket money used to go for that you see really. But anyway I managed it and then I le}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13316472\charrsid14840390 \{ILLEGIBLE\}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
 and then I went as between maid. Oh dear, that was worse than ever. Between maid. I went to - Black Notley that was and I had - I - went in a donkey cart there to Black Notley, to take me little tin - 
truck of luggage, and that was worse than ever there, I was between maid and there was the cook I had to wait on and the houseparlourmaid I had to wait on. Well I had to get up in the morning, light this big range, do the flues, and they used to have stee
l
 on those ranges those days, they had - all had to be cleaned just so and all this black leading, and I used to have to go and do all the doorsteps. And - then I used to - the time I'd done that I used to have to come back for the kitchen and the breakfas
t
, the cook had done the breakfast. And I used to come back and have to do all the washing up, and I used to have go upstairs then and help the - housemaid, make the beds. And - do all sorts of - clean the - I had all the dirtiest of work to do you know, c
l
ean - 'cos - they did have baths that day, and then there used to be a basin in the bedroom, washbasin and jug, I used to have to do all that, and help - whatever she wanted to do, then I used to come downstairs again and do the vegetables for lunch, and 
-
 then there was other jobs to keep the kitchen clean and the scullery clean and clean all the knifes and - that. Then after lunch there'd be all lunch things again, and - used to be - clean shoes, clean the windows. And - then I was supposed to get dresse
d
 then for tea, but - I wasn't always done because it seems to be - then I used to have to churn the - make the butter, do all the churning - do the butter 'cos it was like a farmhouse as well, and then there would be the - then I had to learn to wait - ta
b
le. And one night she said I'd got to go in and wait tables, still got me print frock on. She sent me out quicker than I went in. 'Cos I'd still got me print frock on. And I done that once on twice on her, and I thought, yes, you may, I'm doing all this w
o
rk, I ain't always going to wait at table at that time of night 'cos I've got all the dinner things to wash up. And - the cook - above all things, she used to be a cook nursemaid you see, which made such a lot of work for me. She used to take the baby out
 
in the - trap, and - 'course I was left to do all the dirty work and that, and one day I let - she made a pie and - and I began to let it burn, I forgot about it too, because I was doing something else, my word, didn't she get onto me. I said, I can't be 
everywhere at once. I had three months of that, and I wouldn't stop another day there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What was the mistress like there then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh, she's very strict, oh she was strict. Oh she - I had to go round the carpe I don't know how many times. You get that off and - get that off. Well, I mean it was cruel the work those days. And - anyway I stopped there there months and away I came home.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Can I ask you some more questions about there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did the mistress like to know about your personal life at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh I'd never let it out. If I - if I went out I had to go and ask. I was never in - I don't think I went out from the time I went there 'til I came home. Never - only to church on the Sunday - Sunday - afternoon, that's all I was allowed 
out, to the village church and then I had to come back again. Well it was very hard that was - that - place was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you eat in the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, with the others. With - with the cook and the - housemaid, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did they give you the same food as the mistress had or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Well, practically, we lived very well there, but - I will say because they had all this nice new butter and there used to be meat and - they used to - do their own hams and bacon and eggs you see, they - I lived very wel
l there. I will say. But it was the hardness of the work you see and I was only about - fifteen. Fifteen then you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What time would you get to bed there then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh about ten o'clock at night, about ten o'clock at night. Mm. But it was very hard going, well I stopped there three months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did they call you by your christian name?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh yes, Agnes they used to call me. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What did you have to call her then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh madam. Then I left there then I - I came home, and they wanted - the 
same family really, that was - though it was brother - that was a brother that lived a Notley and that was a sister at Wickham Bishops. Well this sister at Wickham Bishops was left without a maid, so would I go as a step - stop gap for a little while. But
 I went and I was quite happy there, but it was very lonely. I'd got nowhere to go, no friends, no nothing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You were the only one there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, the cook as well. And - I stayed there - six weeks, and she begged of me to stay on. She said, you - you
've done more than any other girl has done for your age here. And I said, I was learnt - all the work, to wait on the table and all that at this other place you see. And she said, oh do stop. So I said, no, I'm afraid not, I said, no, I'm afraid not, I ca
nnot, I said, and I cannot get home to see my parents. So I left.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Were there shorter hours there then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. And - oh yes, they was quite - you know - I done just as I liked and cleaned the rooms as I liked - and they never said anything to me. As long as I done me work I was all right you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You could go out there, you were allowed out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh yes, I'd go out, and - the - gardener there was very good, they said, come to me when you come out if you like, we'll give you a cup of tea, and I 
used to go to their house and they were very nice to me. Very nice they was. But it was - lonely really because I couldn't see me parents and - it was - I couldn't - poach on these - gardeners every time I went out every - you know, one Sunday was one mor
n
ing and one Sunday was in the afternoon, well we had to go to church as well. 'Cos there was nothing done much on a Sunday 'cos it was a vicarage you see, and - but - I couldn't - go to them every time 'cos I'd got not enough money to offer 'em for me foo
d you see, not much. You didn't earn much money. 'Cos even when I left at - the manor house I was only getting ten shillings a week then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you eat separately at the vicarage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, with the other cook, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What was the food like there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh not bad. No. Jolly good really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 The same as the vicar got?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes. Yes, they didn't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13316472\charrsid14840390 treat}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390  us bad at all, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did they do their own baking and that kind of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh yes, the cook had to do all the cooking, yes, yes. I re
member once we had - a - about - thirteen or fourteen - parsons as they call them now, came to dinner at night. Oh dear, that was a night, the poor cook and me getting all this stu ready. And there was a big thunderstorm come, and the hail stones, it was 
i
n the middle of June. And - I had to clear the hailstones as big as that. Oh they broke all the greenhouse and that. 'Course years ago - we had better summers. And we get now, we used to - they had very hot summers to what we get now and the winters used 
to be colder than what we got now. The seasons are quite different to what we had when - as a child, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did they grow their own vegetables and so on in the greenhouses then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh yes. Yes. Oh yes. Lamps. That was the time, had to do all the lamp
s for all the rooms. Oh - and the wicks had to be in for all these - these - glass chimneys you know like used to clean - they all had to be filled every day. Oh every room had to have a can - a lamp in it, then there used to be candles. Oh dear, it used 
to be a work. I roget how many - bedrooms there was in that house. There's a daughter - as well, but - they were very.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 There was an older daughter living there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. Yes. She was out - I don't know what she done, she used to come home weekends. But she was very nice she was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You felt they took an interest in you as a person?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. Yes they did, yes, they treated you - you know, not as - not as a slave. No. Quite different to the brother's wife, she was a tartar she was, yes. She was. Yes
. Then I left there, and then I went to - I came home, then I went to the Manor House, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Living in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Living in, yes, living in both times, and I was there 'til - my mother was taken ill, and it was just be - just before the war, and I had to 
go home and she died, she had strokes and she died you see, so - didn't go out anymore to service, no, I - I stopped home with me father 'til he married. No, I married first. I married first. Then he married and he went off. We came up here to live you se
e and I - I married in 1919.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Were you not doing any work after you came home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No. No. No. None - none of the wives used to go out to work like they do nowadays. Never went out - unless it was field work, they'd want us on the fields you see. 
They used to have their own maids in the big houses you see. Well they can't get them now can they. Used to have all - at the Manor there used to be nine of us in the house.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 This is the last place you were at?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 The Manor. Manor, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Can you tell me about life there, what it was like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh it was - we used to make our own fun there. There used to be butler, footman, cook, kitchen maid - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1900562\charrsid14840390 upstairs}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390  housemaid, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1900562\charrsid14840390 downstairs}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390  housemaid, which I was, and - used to be lady's maid, that's seven
, and then we used to have occasionally help come in the house, and - oh we used to - have - you know, fun really, we used to make our own fun but we used to work hard, we used to have to get up and - I was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1900562\charrsid14840390 downstairs}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390  housemaid of course I used to have to 
- do the dining room first, twenty-two chairs to dust before - sweep all the carpet, dust these twenty-two chairs before breakfast, do the fireplace and it was all brass, all brass fenders. And then the - butler used to bring in the breakfast and that wel
l
 while - while he was having breakfast I used to have to go and do the drawing room. That was all pink carpet with white mat. And - all pictures and there was one table in the - sort of in the middle, that was all little bits of silver, and - then there w
a
s this cat as I told you about as well, and then - after that they come out into the drawing room after I'd finished that. I used to have to do the front hall, that was a big place that was, all these big stone flags, and - one side was these big - stone 
f
lags, the other side was a big carpet, and then there was a big fireplace with the - oh nearly as long as this table with the - fire things and they used to have - burn logs of wood in that, well that length, and of course, worst of it was when the - fron
t
 door was open all these - ash - used to flay everywhere. But - and then there was the billi - his library to do after then. His library I had to do, and there was all books and his - all his stuff in there. Well after I'd done that I used to have to go a
n
d do the billiard room, they used to play billiards in there, used to be the billiard room to do. Well then that used to be - once a time I used to have to go and - change and - and - very often I used to have to help the butler, footman, wait at table yo
u
 see, I used to have to carry the things - things from the kitchen to the - dining room, and they used to have to stand there the whole time, wait on the - people. Sometimes we used to have a lot there weekends and stayed there and during the week. And - 
so it was. But we used to have good food there. We used to have good food, we - the servant's hall, we used to have servants hall, we always used to sit down together in there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 All the servants together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, all the servants together. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 There wasn't a separate place for the butler?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh they used to have their pantry for their silver and all that you see, and they used -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 But they didn't eat apart?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, they used to eat with us, the butler used to be at the head of the table
, and the cook this seat and we others used to be at the sides.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Was it sort of home baking there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh, the cook had to do everything yes. Of course and they used to grow the - all their own vegetables, they used to come in you see. There used to 
be pheasants and - all sorts, 'cos he used to own all these farms you see, Flannery did, used to own - own 'em all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Home brewing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
They didn't do the - no. They didn't do the brewing there, they used to do the washing - and that, but not the brew
ing no, they used to buy all their own wines, used to be the cellar there. It was only the butler had the - no, the butler didn't have the keys to the cellar. He used to keep 'em himself. Flannery did, he used to keep 'em himself, but if he wanted a speci
al wine he used to give the keys to the butler, the butler used to have to go down to get it. He wasn't allowed to keep the keys. I suppose he thought he'd go and drink some of it up. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Do you remember anything about the guests that came to stay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh yes-, some of the guests were very nice, there was - have you heard Foot Mitchel. No, I suppose you haven't, MP, well he - you - I think he's - son is still - I don't know if he's still MP but you do read in the paper, but he used to come and stay t
here, at that - then used to be - there used to be the shooting season and it used to be full up then, the shooting season. Flannery used to ask you see - 'cos they used to keep gamekeeper as well, and used to be all these shoots, big shoots you see and -
 and the gamekeeper used to have to go off to the post with all these pheasants after they'd finished, and they used to be sent off by post to different people. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you hear what they were talking about when you were waiting on them?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh yes,
 you could hear what they was talking about. Mm. Do you - the Ti - do you think - you've heard about the Titanic haven't you. Yes, well he used - he half of that - he was in that - that was his - work or his new - off a way he had a book, and I don't know
 
what happened, he give me that book and I can't remember but he - he was - to do with the cables, Flannery was, he used to go up to town you see, and - I used to go up to town with them when they went they'd got a London house as well. Wasn't I pleased wh
en I got back here again, I -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Why didn't you like it in London then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
I didn't mind it being in the London - but it was the traffic I didn't like, you know, the - and - he used to go - to the stations first of all in the - pony an trap and used t
o go by train. Well then the cars come out you see, and they us to go by car, that's what I couldn't - bear, the cars. Couldn't bear the cars all. No. Cars - oh, I - wasn't I glad - specially when I used to sit in the and wait - and there'd be a horses he
ad come right near me here, and I couldn't bear horses. I couldn't bear horses, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you get out in the evenings in London at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No. Only just to - you know, occasionally we used to go out in the aft - I used to go out in the afternoon but I - I - didn't like it. I - in - London, not to go out by myself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You never went out to a music hall or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh I used to go {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Shaftesbury Avenue{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} sometimes, yes, to a theatre there in the afternoon. Lady Flannery'd say - here's a
 ticket Candler, she used to call me me surname then - here's a ticket Candler, you go so and so will you. She was very good in that way, yes. Yes, very good - and I saw all the bill then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Any other kind of entertainments you got in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 The 
cinemas, she used to - buy - she was very good for that, she used to get tickets for the cinema for us. Mm. Yes. But of course there was only two of us up there, there's the cook and myself but the cook used to be - up there all the time, at the summers -
 at the - London house, you see, it was called Summers Place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You mean they had a complete set of servants in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Only the cook up there you see, and I - from - I from this house had to go up with them to - wait at table and all that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 So you were rather special?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes. Yes, I had to go up - up there with them, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You had a rather personal relationship with her then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes, yes, oh I used to have to do up her frocks and all like that you know. Mm. Yes, she used 
to take me up hundreds - I say hundreds of miles I've been up and down there, used to go up - sometimes she'd say, Candler, I think you ought to have a rest, stay up in London the weekend \{ILLEGIBLE\} work down home. Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 She was very considerate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, she was, yes. I used to like her very much, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did she talk to you quite a lot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, she would, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What sort of things did she talk about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Well she used to talk about, you know - she was very fond of cats and of course
 - and I was very fond of the cat - of the cat and that and - she'd talk about - oh we used to have - well tell you one thing we used to do, we used to have to wear black in the winter, black frocks in the afternoon in the winter, Summertime we had grey f
r
ocks. Grey frocks, with a - little - pretty aprons you know, but we still had to have these hight collars and caps on. With caps on, yes. But we did have that difference summertimes you see, black looked awful summertime, and we did have grey - frocks. Mm
.
 But - she was very nice, you know, she'd come in if she'd been to a - anything, oh you must go and see it Candler, she'd say, and then she'd buy a ticket you see, for me to - for me to go and see, yes. 'Cos she used to dye - have a - go to the hairdresse
s, she used to spend a lot of time at the hairdressers and that, she'd have her - hair all dyed, auburn they call it now. And that, and she used to be powdered, oh she used to look ever so nice, she used to look lovely when she was dressed up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 It took her a long time dressing up did it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Every evening would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. Yes. Yes. And you'd have to go up and - do all her back you know. Mm. These low evening dresses they used to - wear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 They say that some of those peop
le at that time wouldn't have been able to do their hair by themselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, they wouldn't, no. No. They couldn't, no. She used to go out - practically every day you know - and have her hair all - done, and that, she used to be very nice really. Mm. A
nd she used to think a lot of the poor - in the village here. She was - she used to go and visit 'em. Oh yes, she would, she'd go and - when the boys started - when the war broke out first - it first started he made - because they didn't get soldiers, the
y
 didn't get - the same money as they did when they was working you see, and he made all the village boys their money up. He did. Yes, and not many - done that you know. He was good in that way. Mm. But - Sir Fortescue, when I think of that - he - he thoug
ht a lot of himself really. Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did she take an interest in your sort of moral welfare?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes, she used to - you know - what - what we liked and what we didn't like and - and - and that, she used to - say look after yourselves and all that but - s
he - used to visit us and that - one day I didn't announce one properly, that's the only time ever she told me off. I think. Mm. I opened the drawing room door, and I never said who was coming, I - the lady just walked in, and of course I was told off tha
t day. Tell you the truth I couldn't pronounce her name, that was why. She told me her name, I thought, I shall never pronounce that, so I wouldn't say anything, I just let the lady walk in. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did they have a sort of fixed time for callers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Ye
s. Oh yes. Yes. Yes. Fixed time for callers. Always a card you see, they always had a card. Always left that card on the - hall table in a - it used to be a silver slaver there, oh be - used to be lovely there. Mm. And then you see - Lady Flannery used to
 have to re - go back - and call on her, that's how they used to do it. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Was it the same in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and down here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. Yes, just the same, yes. Just the same. Yes, I say I shall always remember her getting herself up for the - does you know. M
m. She used to look very sweet. But - oh hair - the hair is done very much now like it used to be then, all up high here and that - and she used to have a knob here you know. Oh dear. And she - in bed at night we used to laugh at night - because she used 
t
o have this - a hat on her hair, she used to put her hair all in these rollers, used to be - night cap, well it - like a dust cap really and it used to be all edged with lace all round here and that, and her face used to be all cream, you never saw anythi
ng like it. Yes. Keep herself looking nice you know, cream. But - 'cos there used to be a dressing room you see next door for him, he used to have a dressing room you see, yes. For his clothes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 He took his valet up to London then did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No. 
No. I used to have to see after his clothes. Mm. Yes. Just brush 'em and that, you know. Mm. And they all had to be looked after well then they came back you see. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did she insist on your coming in at a certain time in the evening?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh yes. O
h yes, you always had to come in at a certain time, yes. In fact I didn't go out much. Well up here - if you wanted to go out to post a letter you had to go to - an ask - if you could go up the village to post a letter for yourself. See you - you always h
ad to be - you had your certain time out. And if you did want to go out - otherwise you have to - you had to go in and ask could you just go so and so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 In the time that you were allowed to go out could you do what you liked?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 She didn't want to know where you'd been?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No, she didn't want to know. You was allowed out from half past two 'til - ten o'clock at night. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 That's once a week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Once a week, yes. And then every other Sunday. So the other ones could - go out you see, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Were you allowed to have any visitors?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, well you could have your mother and father but nobody else, no. My mother come up once to see me, that was all, and then I showed her over the house. She nearly fainted - when I told
 her what I had to do, all those chairs and that before breakfast. 'Cos after our little house you see and then - she that she could hardly believe it. She said, do you have to do all that? I said, yes. LI do all that I said, before you're up. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Di
d the mistress supervise the housework personally or did she really leave it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
She left it to you, yes, she left - she used to go out every morning, orders what she wanted for lunch to the cook. Oh yes, the kitchen had to be just so at ten o'clock eve
ry morning you see. 'Course I didn't have anything to do with that but - and then if she - the cook wanted any store there used to be the store cupboard you see, if the cook wanted anything out she hadn't got in the kitchen - she used to unlock the door a
nd the cook used to get the stuff out and - and take it to the kitchen, then 1 Lady Flannery used to lock it up again and take the key with her. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 She took less direct interest then than the other people you worked for?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes. She was more 
freer. Freer up there than you was - with the others really. Long as you done your work it was all right you see, yes. And you was all dressed up to - the time, you know. Get ready to wait and that but - you done your work and got your uniform on we used 
to call it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Do you remember any other sort of occasions having an amusing time there?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Well we used - us girls, we used to play - cards in the kitchen - in the servants hall you see, 'cos we used to have a fire on on our own. And - we used to pla
y cards or - anything or do our knitting and sewing and all like that you see. We used to - that was - that was a servants hall. If the butler wanted to do anything on his own, didn't want to join us - well he'd got his pantry you see and the footman. Yes
.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Was there any music?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, we didn't have no music.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Singing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No. No, we didn't do that, 'cos - they might hear through the other way.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
They didn't have any special occasions like Christmas where you'd all join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh we u
sed to have our special Christmas us girls - and the servants all did and they didn't disturb us. They didn't ring the bell, we used to have a whole - oh longer than this room, all row of bells and each had got number on. If they wanted this bell used to 
r
ing you see in whichever room they was in. We used to have to look up - which room it was you see and where we had to go. See, like that. But - on Christmas Day we had our - own day - I think they had theirs at night and we had ours at lunchtime, and they
 
wouldn't ring a bell at all while we was - up - on our own you see, that was our Christmas, yes. Oh no, they'd see that we wasn't disturbed, yes. But I mean sometimes you'd just sit down to your dinner perhaps - ordinary day, and the bell'd ring - go and 
away you had to go you see. Yes, butler or footman or - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1900562\charrsid14840390 upstairs}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390  housemaid or the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1900562\charrsid14840390 downstairs}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390  one you see, whichever the bell - whichever rooms you looked after you ha}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13316472\charrsid14840390 d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390  - had to go, whichever bell rung. I don't know what they'd think of today I'm sure. No. About my father giving me my first }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1900562\charrsid14840390 tomatoes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390  out of the garden did I? Well he gave - he used to grow these tomatoes you see }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1900562\charrsid14840390 it}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
 in the garden, and he said - the first one like - 'cos we used to have such hot summers then and the first one - right, there y
ou are Aggie, he said, you eat that. I had one bite, I said, oh dad, I don't like that. And I've never eaten another tomato in my life. It put me against it. And he could eat them just like that, pick them and eat them, well - I couldn't. No. My mother us
ed to like them too but I didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you ever have to look after children while you were in service?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
I did once, yes, there was a lady up the village, she was rather - she had a \{ILLEGIBLE\} rather late in life, and - when I came home from school dinner time she used to say, you might take {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Frances{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 out for me, it's only - if - if it was only quarter an hour in her pram. She was a big fat woman. And I used to take her most din times - out in a pram. I used to take her home - to my house and I had m
y dinner you see and used to leave her outside in the pram and I used to bring her back again. If I was too early I used to drive her up and down the road in front of the house you see. That's the only baby I ever looked after. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You never looked after children in the houses then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No. No. Only used to take this - just this one out, that was all, mm.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you have any other part time jobs while you were still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No. 'Cos you see - we - if - when the seasons come round 
we used to have go in the field - and single out - didn't have sugar beet those days, it used to be mangol - mangol - sweedes - or turnips, in the fields, we used to have to go and single those out, used to get seven and six an acre for that. Do a whole a
cre for seven and sixpence. Yes. And - but - what we used to do see and then the - it used to be the gleaning, and then the acorning. See? I have told you about those haven't I? Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 I wondered if there were any other little jobs like taking the child out?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. No. That - that's all I used to do was that one children 'cos - then you see after school at night we used to have to walk right way after milk you see. Mm. When that used to be dark like. Mm. When we came home. 'Course then we - we used to
 have to clean our shoes and - overnight ready for the morning. Mm. Except when I got in the pond.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
I was wondering about these houses where you were a servant, supposing one of the maids was courting, would they interfere?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh no. No, they'd never interfere. No. They'd never interfere, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 But they wouldn't allow the man to come up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 They wouldn't allow them to come into the house, no. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 That was the same with all the places was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, all the places I've been to, yes, 
they never allow you - they could see you home to the gate and that was all, that's as far as they dare go. Mm. Man's not allowed in the house, no. And the same as your mother and father years ago - same as - you was never left alone with a young man in t
h
e house, never left alone, no. No, if you - I didn't take many home but I did take home a - I used to go out with a cousin of mine a little while but - you was never - left alone. Never. No, and - of course - when I went out with me husband - and that's a
bout the only ones I went out with. But they was very strict of that, oh, mustn't be left alone. No. Not 'til - that was very sacred you see, don't go on as they do of today. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 If you were in service it was much more difficult to meet people wasn't it?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. It was, yes. Yes it was, yes. I used to - how I met my husband was - I was at the Manor you see and - and when the butler was out - I used to have to come up to the post and post the letters you see. Well I used to come up you see there used
 to be a cycle shop opposite the Post Office, well they - of course they used to whistle after you. And - and then he in time he actually come - home with me you see from the post and that was my - I used to look out and that how I got to go with him. I k
ept with him ever since. And - of course - they used to tease me 'cos I used to go out with him 'cos he'd got these two artificial feet. Well the gardener used to up there. He said, going about, he said, with that no }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1900562\charrsid14840390 toothy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390  man, he said, can't understand yo
u. So I said, well, I feel sorry for him - and that - and - my mother - she did - my father did take to him you see and - and never said any more and they said - they kept worrying if they - 'cos my mother died before I did marry, but they worried how I s
hould get on. Said, well, look, mum and dad, if he can't work I can perhaps. Mm. See? So that was. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Where would you go out to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
I used to cycle, used to cycle about you see, used to - he could cycle and I could cycle, and we used to go different places. Sometimes we'd cycle to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Braintree{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}. And - the afternoon out we used to always have to be in at a time, and - we used to - me husband used to come up to me father's you see in the evening after he'd left off work and he'd - didn't have time to go 
far you see not in those days, no. Only when you had your holiday. We used to have a fortnight's holiday every year. Fortnight's holiday every year. Well that was the time then we used to - go out for days together perhaps. We used to go to - went to Frin
ton one year, and went to - cycled - cycled there and cycled back. Mm. That's how we got on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You liked it by the sea then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Beg pardon? Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you just sit on the beach?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Just on the beach, daren't go in it. Well I used to p
addle but not to - have to go on the boats, no fear. No. No. That's - the first time I went - had ever seen the sea that was, when - when I was about eighteen and I tell you - I tell you the - first time I ever went in a train was when I used to go up wit
h
 the Flannery's, that was 19 - 16 I suppose, 19 - 17, yes. Yes. But my - my daughter here, she won't go in a train at all. She won't. No. But - I used to like the underground, I - now my young daughter don't like the underground trains but I didn't used t
o mind where I went. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What was the year when you left the Flannery's then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 1918. 1918. I married in 1919. Mm. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
When you went out to Braintree was there anything interesting to do in Braintree?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, not like there is now, you 
just walked round, there's hardly anybody walking about you know but we just looked in - in the shops to see what you buy - I remember my mother giving me three and sixpence, now, she said, you can walk to Braintree and buy what you like. What do you thin
k
 I bought with that three and sixpence? My book, hymn - prayer book with that. Three and sixpence. And she said, whatever made you buy that, this - this hymn - prayer book? I said, because I liked it. And - I don't think I've got - still got it. Anyway I 
g
ot this prayer and hymn book, it's - it's in a case you know, but - the hymns were separate and the - prayer book was separate just in the case. And that just took my fancy. She said, fancy you buying that like that, I thought you'd have bought something 
different. I said, no, I just liked that and - then I walked home again. That was a young girl and meself next door walked to Braintree and back. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you ever go into a pub for a drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Not even when you were out in Braintree?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No. We never had nothing, only what we took with us. No. We took a - a sandwich with us and - and that's all we had. Mm. 'Cos there was no - thermos flasks those days. No. No, we used to take a sandwich and biscuit and that was all and we used to walk
 round walk - and come back and that was that. Mm. No tea shops then there like there is now. No. No. Things were quite different.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You were carrying on with church but you gave up the Sunday school I suppose?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, when I went to service, yes. Mm.
 Well I - I was in the choir you see, and - I carried on with that 'til I left school. Yes, I was baptized down at Shalfor church. I was confirmed down there and I was married down there. Mm. Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you have to save up for a long time before getting married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. Well yes, because the money didn't go so far, although - if you got a hundred pounds you was very rich, see, those days, you know. I didn't - we didn't have any husband and I didn't have that amount of money when we married. No. We onl
y had about fifty between us. Yes. And we thought - and we bought our home for that. Yes. Yes. That couch, that still what you're sitting on what we bought. Yes. And I wouldn't part with it now. I - that suite of furniture there's the chairs in the other 
room - that couch and two armchairs - only gave sixteen guineas for that. And when I had it recovered - don't know how many year ago, it cost me twenty-two pound to have it covered. It only cost me six - only cost me sixteen }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1900562\charrsid14840390 guineas}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390  to have it, I mean it's 
still in decent order and that, see, look. But I like - I like it you see because it's - you can get your feet up on it. But - the things of today you just can't get your feet up can you? You know, if you're not feeling very well you can lay there and get
 your feet right up. Mm. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did your parents help you at all in setting up a home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, no, no, they never - any - well my - I had - my father married again, and he - what he didn't want I had, but it was very little, the table, not this table but another table, 'cos they was all wooden tables years ago, and a kneading }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1900562\charrsid14840390 touch}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
 he gave me what they used to - but my mother never did make bread kneading trough, well the kneading trough now is still in the big house, and it was all hand made you see, 
all the furniture here years ago - even the chairs were hand made. They used to have drills in them and - the kneading troughs and - those oak legs you see and white tops and they used to be scrubbed every week, those tops of those tables. Used to have a 
c
loth over them you see. Just a cloth over 'em. And I had that when I married from my father. And I also had the iron bedstead, well of course - afterwards I got - different to that Yes. But the furniture was made those days because I mean they - they make
 - all that couch - I mean that's been fifty years ago since that was bought, I mean it's not bad now is it. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Was it the Manor or the Hall, the last place you went to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 The Manor. The Manor.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did they have somebody there who was making thin
gs for them, like a carpenter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, they didn't have a carpenter, no. They used to have a - the - builder come round you see, Wicks, he used to go round and do things for them but - they used to have a needlewoman you see, she used to do all the needl
ework, all the mend of the - sheets and - all like - if they wanted mending, and make the curtains a that you see. She was living in, yes. 'Cos you see there was a lot of us, us to - and then there used to be - wash days - it got so up there they didn't h
ave no washing done, all the washing went out - well the man used to have a great by wicker basket you see with all these sheets and tablecloths in, there used to be a - woman in the village used to do the lot then. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 So what about the first place that you went to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh that was done at home. That - that was done at home, yes. That was done a home. Yes. That was done at home. My daughter just coming in. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Did they take any interest in politics, do you remember any talk about politics when you were in service ever, were you interested in that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, no, they didn't talk much about it, no. No. No, not politics, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You didn't take much interest yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No. I didn't, no. No. No, I didn't, no, no. Phyllis, are you there?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Could you describe the kitchen at this place, what sort of equipment they had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh - don't talk - they had a big - big old dresser as big as this, but it was all white wood and had to be scrubbed all the time, and all the plates was all put along 
all - all got their crest on. He had a special crest, you know, they did those days, and - silver was all the same with all the crest on it, and then they had this - big white table with - where - cook used to do all her cooking on that be scrubbed after 
e
verything was made it had to be - kitchen maid used to have to do that, and - then there was this big fireplace, and that used to have to heat the water - poor kitchen maid used to have to be up early 'cos she used to have to cook the breakfast and do all
 
the heating of the bathwaters as well, and if she wasn't up at a certain time the water wasn't a certain heat she used to have to go on the carpet - more than what we did. And she used to have to pluck the pheasants and - skin the rabbits you know, and do
 
all the washing up, and - all - all the kitchen was all these big flagstones. All big flagstones. Kitchen was. Nothing at all - there was I think just a mat in front of the stove, but that was all there was on the floor in the kitchen. That was very cold 
really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 But it was a range they cooked on was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. Used to be ovens - to each side. This fire in the middle you see and used to be big - all these flues to do - for the kitchen maid, used to have to do them once a week and all this steel all on them. Oh -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did they roast anything on the fire?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, always used to be in the ovens, yes. Used to make all our own cakes and all their own puddings and all like that you know. But - 'cos and - that had - that all had to be just so when lady Flannery come out at ten o'clock in the morning. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 There was no electricity in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. Gas - gas. Calor gas. Gas. And that - they used to have make their own you see then, used to make their own. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did they have gas anywhere else that you worked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, no. Well - where - where - wherever else I went they was all - lamps, you see like this light. But that place did have calor gas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 They had gas lights as well you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, they used to have them on the walls, yes, us
ed to have them - same as two here and - that - two - two here and two here, used to be about four on each wall and of course the butler had to go round and light the whole lot and see that was all safe at night you see. There was too much gas used that -
 I didn't like it at all. No. So - us girls, if we sat up a little later, we used to have candles, we used to buy our own candles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Would they have told you off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. Used too much gas. Yes. Carbide you see it used to be done from, carbide. Mm. Those days. Oh and didn't that used to smell too, I didn't like it, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did they keep any animals for eating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Pigs. Pigs. Oh yes, the pigs, they used to keep pigs and - used to all have to be dried you know, these hams and that used to have to be dried, yes, and then they used to have roast pork 'course the poor cook used to be busy at it then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did they have hens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, they didn't keep chickens up there. Don't know for why, they didn't keep chickens, no. Only just pigs. Mm. Coachman I
 think used to look - or was it the game - under gamekeeper used to look after the pigs, 'cos you see used to be swill, there's always - all vegetables - pigs were fed them days different to what they are now you see, used to come in every day for what's 
called the swill, used to be put in pails you see. Mm. Yes. 'Cos they used to - have a lot of bones you see too from the butchers for soup to give out to the poor you see. Yes. The cook used to have to do all that you see, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Was that just in winter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. I don't think they had - made - Lady Flannery when it was - saw anybody - poor, they'd have a drop of soup, they used to have to go, yes. Somebody used to have take it up, the men mostly used to have to take that, the coachman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did she ever do that in London?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, not in London. No. Not in London, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 It was a much smaller house in London was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh yes. Well it was - no - down the - basement, used to be basement for us girl - the cook and myself. Used to be the kitchen
 and the servants hall down there and then used to have to go upstairs to the front rooms. And - then there used to be the dining room on the - first floor, dining room. And - go through that way and there used to be a - Sir Fortescue's study and there us
e
d to be the - cook - the chauffeur's bedroom. Then you go up another flight of stairs and used to be all - this part was drawing room. And you go up another flight of stairs and there used to be a bedroom - her bedroom and the dressing room and the toilet
.
 Go up another flight of stairs, used to be the visitors bedrooms, up there. Go up another flight of stairs and used to be our bedroom. Yes, talk about getting tired during the day. Oh it was tiring all those stairs. And it was all white paint and green c
arpet. They had to be washed down every week. You see, you - it was the dust - and that in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 that it - you know - used to be terrible for dust. Mm. I used to wash those down with - a leather and drop of paraffin in water. And it used to be just as quick as dusting them really. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you have a separate bathroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh we - we had to use their bathroom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 But they did have a proper bathroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 They did have a prop - proper bathroom up at Summers Place, yes. In the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} house, but - us - we used to have to - there was only bathroom up there. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Down here did they have a bathroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
All the servants had a bathroom to theirselves. Yes. And each - dressing room up at the Manor had a bath. Yes. It did.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Where did you sleep at the Manor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh at the Manor we had - a wing, for us girls, you know, there was a wing - for - for the kitchen and the - butlers and all that, and up above you see was all the servants - bedrooms. Yes, up above. Yes. And in - through the double - door
 we used to call 'em there was all their departments you see. Yes. All that, yes. In the - - butler's room there used to be a big - thing like that with all steel doors, it's all built in and concreted and all lined in you see, used to be built in, that u
sed to have to be packed away every night. Every night, yes. Used to be packed away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Why was the silver packed away then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Because afraid of it - lose - you know, I suppose it be - anybody come in and broke in 'cos they'd got a lot of silver those days. All these huge candle }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1900562\charrsid14840390 stick}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
. All solid silver. And all silver dishes. And that - all - everything was - oh and then there's all the spoons, forks, you know, cutlery, everything's - silver - masses of silver they had up there. Mm. Well I often wonder
 what happened to them - you know - I know the - son took over but - what happened to it when the sale was I don't know. No. No. Oh it was - that was a job to clean. And I've seen the butler - up there, he'd get a spoon, if there was a scratch on it, he w
o
uld have to get it out with his thumb like that, he'd press it and get it out. Yes. And it was all cleaned. Yes, it was - marvelous what they had to do. And this - silver in the drawer in the tables, all little - fiddling bits, all what she'd picked up at
 different places you see. Yes. She was telling me. Snuff boxes and all - silver. Mm. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 He was a huntsman was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. He didn't go out hunting, no. No. He didn't go out hunting at all, no. No. Only used to go up and down - I tell you he was in
 this cable concern. His job was, he was a big - man really, and then of course he was MP as well, you see, yes, he was an MP as well, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 So you'd hear them talking about politics at the table would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Well not very much at - you know -
 visitors was there, but - they didn't talk a lot about politics, no. Sometimes they would but - not a lot, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did he shoot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh yes. There used to be shooting days, they used to - poor cook used to have to make big meat puddings - and the coach
man used to have to come and take 'em all up in the barrow. He used to have 'em up at the Dog Inn. They didn't come to the house, all these meat puddings used to be made and all the - the men that shoot used to have this at the Dog with a drink you see. M
m
. Used to be the day, all these meat puddings. Mm. But she didn't stint you with food, I will say that, that - whatever places I - went to I wasn't stinted with food. No. No. No. 'Cos I mean - some of them treated you as if you got a - not have anything y
ou know, 'cos I've heard some - say, oh we only had bread and marg for our tea. See? But we always had butter. Always. Where I've been. Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Were you fed at the first place when you were just going by the day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Mm. Yes, yes, good food there. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You had dinner there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Whatever they had I had. Mm. Yes. I did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 I don't mean at the Hall, I mean at the first place with the }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1900562\charrsid14840390 acres}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
I know, yes, I had just what she had, yes, only I had mine in the kitchen and they had theirs in the dining room. But she used to cut off mine just like they had. Mm. Yes. Yes, she was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 It must have been lonely sitting there by yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes, it was a bit 'cos after sitting with me mum and dad. Yes. I often think about her, you know, but - didn'
t see her name much in the papers, she went under another name you see, they do these actresses don't they, they go names - married names, Mrs Bruce Smith but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did she mix with people round there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. Not much. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 They didn't entertain?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No callers at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No. No callers, she used to come down you see and - this Bill Compton you see as he was called, he used to - come there I think. There's a - still a Compton in the acting world, I often wonder whether to write to him to know if he'd any relation. Mm.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did they go to church?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No, they didn't go to church, no. No. In fact she used to be - I think learning the - what she had to learn then down here but she used to go - go in here rooms there for 
hours you know, I think she was learning her bit of - what she had to - say and that. Mm. Yes. She was a nice looking woman she was, very nice. Mm. Yes, very nice she was. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 When you went to church did you sit with the squire and the mistress or 
did you all sit separately?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
We had to sit separate, yes. Yes. Yes. We did, sat separate. But I was in the choir you see. Chir. Mm. We all had our - all our mother and fathers all had the same pews, they had to sit in them pews each Sunday and then th
ey could soon see which wasn't there and which was. If you wasn't there on a Sunday you had to go on the carpet the next day. Why wasn't you at church? Your mother and father? Mm hm. Yes, all the same pews. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What did you think of the vicar?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 V
icar - well he - he was only the same one while I was at Shalford, his name was Lowell, Reverend Lowell and Mrs Lowell - in fact his - daughter-in-law's till lives up here. But - he had one son a coachman and - also - his wife that lives here, and - he ne
arly went potty over a love affair he did. He used to go out with a - a Miss Ling and she gave him up and he nearly went potty over that. And then he went away, and he came - and he married this one what's up here now, he's got two sons. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 That's the son?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes. Yes, that's the son. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 But his father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 He was the vicar, he was the vicar.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What did you think of his sermons, what did he preach like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh - like they do nowadays really, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 It hasn't changed much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, no. Not the sermons no. Only - last a bit longer years ago that what it does now. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did he talk in a fairly simple way that everybody could understand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes.Yes. Yes. \{ILLEGIBLE\}
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You think they do that more now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh yes, more hig
h church now isn't it, altogether, I mean you go - I mean - years ago they never carried a cross like they do now down the church, the choir - there's one in the choir - carries the cross in front of the choir as they walk down the - but they never done t
h
at years ago. No. No. No. No, it's more simple really. Mm. Then. And the tunes we all knew years ago, well now they keep altering the tunes to the hymns don't they. - Mm. Yes, they do. Us old ones don't like it. Oh - I was at - oh I didn't tell you I was 
a
t Porter's Hall just a little while - at Stebbing, I forgot I was at - in service there, and - the - the mistress come out to me and she said, Oh Candler, she said, we shall have to get up, she said, the - he was a Leiutenant I suppose, she said, war has 
b
roke out or - or - and - you'll have to leave. I said, oh - will I? I hadn't been there about - couple of months. And - that was - just - and she has to give up all her home, she gave up her home, and they sold it I think, and - he just went off the war. 
A
nd I thought, oh dear, what shall we do, and so I went home and then I tell you I got the place at the Manor, but - oh it seemed dreadful to see all the boys and that go off you know to war, and then of course - here - I got the Manor - all the boys went 
f
rom here. Think there was eighteen killed from this village. Yes. Names are up in the church any rate. 'Course it was more soldiers in the first war wasn't it, than it was in this war you see, because it was the civilians what was hurt more in the second 
- war, but it was the poor soldiers in the other - my husband's brother was - gassed in the first world war, he was gassed and he came back and he never got over it, he died. Mm. Eldest brother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 So your first visit to London was during the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Do you remember the first day which you went to London?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh - yes I do, I remember that and I thought, oh dear, didn't - it was to be up here like that and then there was the - you know, the zeppelins coming over, and that. There was the
 children running to the church for shelter - from the mews at the back, you see, was a big house and there's the mews at the back, there's the poor mothers got the children going to the church in the crypt - in the - and bugles used to play - and they - 
w
hen they got to go, and then when the all clear came the same was the bugles went again, all clear, and then the little children used to come back - cook and I - used to get in the street - coal cellar was underneath the street you see, we used to go in t
h
ere for safety we would. 'Cos I wouldn't sleep up top of the house then. No. But Lady Flannery and he used to sleep - up there. She used to get her head all covered over with sheets. It's funny really. But it was - you know, it was very scaring at the tim
e 'cos these zeppelins, they made such a noise. And of course and there was Hyde Park, we was near Hyde Park you see and all the guns kept going off as well. It was terrible noise. Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you ever watch the Sunday parade in Hyde Park?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, I re
member - seeing a German spy caught there once. Yes, I was up there one afternoon, I went in there and these - they were all standing in there. There was some people you know standing up, they was all round and they was talking. Forget what they was talki
n
g about now and - all of a sudden the police come and they took all - one away, then - and of course I was by myself and I was half scared so I said to Mrs - Phanton, that was the cook - I said, whatever did they take him away for? She said, I - you'll se
e perhaps in tomorrow's paper - oh well paper - and it was, it was a German spy. Mm. Spy, he was spouting you see and he happened to - talk too much and away they took him off. Yes. Yes. Yes they did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Where exactly were you working in 1911 then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 1911 - well I was - was I still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You hadn't quite left then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, I hadn't, no. No. I hadn't. No. No, not 1911 'cos you see I was born 1897. So I hadn't quite left school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What month were you born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 9th of December, 18 - 18 - yes, I wasn't quite left school in 1911.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 I wondered if you just started work that year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh yes, no, 1914. I was fourteen I meant when I started work. But - so that'd be about 1913 wouldn't it. Twelve or thirteen, yes. I left school when I was - 
just before I was fourteen and then started you see, yes. I was not far off of fourteen when I left, tell you the truth I avoided the exam. I left in the October - no, in the August and I should have went on 'til the September for the exam, and I left the
n, I wouldn't go back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you ever go to any evening classes afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, there was no evening classes those days, no. No. Only the - dancing, our schoolmaster used to learn us dancing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 In the evenings?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, in the evenings, yes. 
I remember my mother used to do my hair up then in the - rolls, just rolls there, and - rolled there, she'd do it up for me. To go dancing. We never had it loose when we danced, so it was just done up in rolls, otherwise it was always hanging down. Mm. Or
 tied back or else plaited. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 That was learning to dance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, learning to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Were there ever any dances?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
There were - we used to - we used to - learn the Lancers and the Vale - Valetta wasn't it, and - what's the other - quad - Quadrilles. What other dance was there Waltz. Waltzes. Used to - just learn - I don't think I could do them now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Were there any dances at the houses that you worked in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. Yes, at the Manor house, the dining room - the dining room up there - was - al
l polished wood with a carpet, well when there was a - when they come there - oh visits, we used to have to move the dining room table into the window, and take - fold the carpet and they used to dance in that room. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 A lot of people came?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Lot of people came then, yes. Yes. Lot of people came.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did he really mix with the sort of country gentry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh yes, they was - hosts of people come from all round, all these Mp's you know, you have to be in and out with them you know, we'd hand them wine and all that and - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did he come from that kind of background himself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes, he did, but - she wasn't quite so well off I don't - she come from - they came from Yorkshire I think I did hear, but her mother used to come - every year 
and stay for a while, she was a dear old lady. But you could see she hadn't been used to all that, you know, no, she hadn't been used to all that, but - they were - very well - you know, all - all the - all the time, yes. And then they used to - I'll tell
 
you another - she used to have two poorer people they used to know in their childhood days, and they used to come and stay up there, they were - called Miss - Tombs - oh forget their name, that - Butterfly was the name, that's right, two Miss Butterfly, a
nd - they used to come and stay, she used to keep them so long you see and they - and that used to help them along you see. She'd keep them in there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 They were sort of ladies in reduced circumstances?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, yes, that's right, yes, yes. But she wa
s very friendly, Lady Flannery was, I mean she - she talked to the poor as - like she would the - the others, you know, she - she'd go in anybody's house and sit down - and that, the poorest they was, they call it poise, you know, she - she'd go and sit d
own and talk to them a that and she'd send 'em coal - if they - she think - think that they wanted coal she'd send them coal. And pea soup. And - used to be a parcel of groceries for them at Christmas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Was that unusual do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, 'cos you wouldn't got nothing of that nowadays you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 But did the people at the Hall do that kind of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 At the -?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Where you were before?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No, not the other places they didn't, no, it was only just here. No. 'Cos I know - 'cos the poo
r people said, yes, they do that 'cos they want the votes. I don't think that was that, I think she used to feel sorry for the people you see Mm. Yes, she - they used to say, oh they won't know us when the voting's over but they did, they - they always us
e
d to raise their hats, it didn't matter who Lord Flannery always used to raise his hat, all - if he didn't raise his hat he used to put his hand up to the people as he passed them by. Mm. Yes. Yes. Dear oh dear, voting days. But now there's nothing of tha
t like that now you know, I mean they don't carry the men about the villages and that, and - you see poster here and there now, but - I know we didn't have the poster years ago but they used to think more of it you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What do you mean by carrying the men about the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes. That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Carrying them in a cart?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, they used to - get the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh, the squire when he was elected?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 I thought you meant there would be a cart load of supporters.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 N
o. No. No. No there wouldn't be, no. No. No. Be nothing of that like; that in the village, no. You just - wait to hear the results and that's that. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Would they go up and hear the result declared then? At Braintree?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, we - we'd just wait 'til it comes through on the - wireless or the -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 I mean in the old days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh well the - I don't know how they used to get to know. I suppose it's when Flannery came home at night - they used to get to know. They had the flag you see - there used to 
be flag, when he was at home - they used to have a flagpole, when he was at home the flag used to be up, if he was away the flag wad down. See? Oh, yes, Union Jack used to be flown. So callers could know if he was home or not you see. Mm. Yes. Yes. Oh dea
r
. Teddy what are you doing - to the puddings, told his mother about the batter pudding. We - we used to have rice - you've got it off haven't you? Rice - a cup of rice in a cloth, boiled in a cloth like we do - do the other puddings and that used to be ne
arly always Saturday dinner 'cos it was easy a cup of rice boiled in this cloth, and we used to have jam or treacle on it. Used to be jolly good. Yes. Charlie Carter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Can you tell me the story again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, I will yes. I'll tell it to you. Charlie 
Carter - see - what else that I haven't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Then there's dancing on the maypole you mentioned too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh yes, about the may - I forgot all about the maypole when we went to school, that was a - we - um - the schoolmaster used to have this and we used
 to learn the maypole and we - it used to braid up beautifully as we was dancing round. I forget how many of us, was it - dozen of us? Think it must have been a dozen of us, we used to have to go all round it you know. There'd be - used to be pairs, a boy
 
and a girl you see and we used to have to go round, then used to change onto the next round, and then you'd go round and change onto the next one, it all braided up lovely. Mm. Then we used to - after it was done - after we'd got no more length of braid w
e used to have to go back the other way round to undo it. Yes. We did. That was always done on Empire Day. Always on Empire Day. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 There weren't any men Morris dancers here then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, no Morris dance - no. No. \{ILLEGIBLE\} the quadrilles and the 
Lancers and that you know. But - mm - no more. Know about Charilie Carter? He walked to Heddicombe station which is four and a half miles with a heavy wheelbarrow to get some leather for making harness - for the saddle maker, and back again. He said to hi
m, how much Charlie? He said, sixpence please. He said, it's worth more than that. So he gave him a shilling. And poor old man, he'd got hardly any shoes to his feet. But any rate he was ever so pleased with the shilling.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Who was Charlie Carter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Didn't I tell you in one of them, he was - the - the man that used to go - play 1 he never done any work only used to have food. Yes. That's the one. Yes. Mm. Yes. That's the one, and he - you know, I remember that was how he'd walk to - Heddicombe statio
n, which is nine miles you see there and back. Yes. And he - and they had barrows then of - course - was not like they are today, they were iron wheels. Yes. And also we - have we got - also we done for - on Empire Day we had the - Maypole, which was very
 
nice, we - he had - I think it was a dozen - on the pole and there used to be a boy and girl together and we used to have to go round, and - and then we'd finish that round and we have to go - change hands like on the next one, 'til all the braid was used
 
up. When it was used up we have to reverse it, right the way round again 'til it was all finished. That was always done on Empire Day, then in the afternoon we had a holiday because it was Empire Day, but - that always had to be done. Mm. OH and then ther
e
 was aniseed balls I forgot about, we had - twenty aniseed balls for a penny, small ones. We had four - oh it was more, twenty for a penny, small ones. We had forty - and that was a ha'penny that should have been - forty for a penny, also my father - he w
ore britches and buckskins for work summertime - trousers with a piece of binder string - tied just below the knees.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 That's like in the phot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. Now what else have I got. Oh and then about the potatoes. You know summers in the garden if we had 
tiny - potatoes or anything - extra small, they used to say, ain't they little darbles. darvaels. Yes. That was - that was a word they used to use. What was that other word? Oh I can't think of it now Oh Gor' blimey they used to say, gor' blimey if anythi
ng happened unusual, oh gor' blimey. That was - anything unusual, that was always the thing. Yes. Well now then out for a day, they used to say - oh, have you got your victuals with you? Say, oh yes, I've got me }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1900562\charrsid14840390 victual}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 s, and that used to be cold tea, bread
 and cheese, because there was no thermos flasks those days you see and they used to take - they used to make the tea like we do, and they used to put it in a pint bottle you see and carry it like that. Mm hm. Mm hm. I think that's about all. Oh then - pu
d
dings - I - forgot to tell you about the - rice pudding we used to have on a Saturday. Used - my mother used to put about a cup office in a - in a cloth like she did other puddings, and used to boil it in a cloth and it used to come out in a shape you see
, and - we used to have that with jam and - or treacle, anything you could get hold of to eat with it. I think that's about -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
The first one was in your schooldays were you expected to go to bed at a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh yes, we had to go to bed at -
 about half past seven. When you got a little older it got a little longer, each time, 'til it was - always went to bed before mother and father, we never had to sit up with them. No. They had their time on their own you know, but - of course when we got 
fourteen, well there you are, we did used to go to bed - only just before them, we was never left downstairs, we always had to be up in bed first.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 How old would you be when you put yourself to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh I should think - oh I was about - ten I shoul
d think when I put - yes, 'cos you see we had candles, and they - so - candlestick you see with the candle in and mother was always afraid you was getting - going to get burnt you see, so we - she always came upstairs with me, and always - we always - alw
ays had to kneel down beside the bed and say me prayers before I got into bed. Mm. That was - that yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Was it your mother that would serve out the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh yes. Yes, my father never done anything. No, he wouldn't cut the meat, we we didn't have 
joints those days 'cos we couldn't afford it, but - used to have stewing beef and - and that make - meat puddings you see, but we never - never really had a joint, only when we had a rabbit, and that was all - done in the oven lovely with onions. Yes. Nev
er remember having a joint. No. Not 'til I went out to service and then saw all these huge legs of lamb, pork and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did she serve your father first like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh yes, father was always first, yes, children was always last, yes. Yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did 
your parents say that if you were hit, if another child hurt you you should hit back or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. She - we - we never used to have to touch each other. No. No. They used to say cross words to you, but - you know, say - like that, but we never - I don'
t ever remember hitting by another child. More than we dare to because the schoolmaster'd cane you if you did. Yes. Yes, the schoolmaster'd cane you, I mean, and anything after tea that you done wrong after tea, anything, if the schoolmaster got to hear o
f it you'd have a caning the next day, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What sort of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Same if you done mischief or anything, you know, what you shouldn't do, yes, but - you - you - more than dare do was to hit anybody else. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 They were watching you out of school as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. Yes. Different to what they are nowadays. Yes. More stricter you see altogether. And we was no worse for it. No. I mean it was good for us really I think, to what they are today, I mean they don't care, they just answer you back don
't they? Mm. Anyhow - more than we dare do was to answer our mother and father back. Or the schoolmaster.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you feel that your mother and father could show affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh yes. Yes. But they - it was in a sort of a - different way somehow, they 
used to - you know, sort of love you and that but it was in a different way of what they do today. Same as of today, oh they buy the children everything they want don't they. Whereas before they just sort of talked to you and that and - take you where the
y could, you didn't go far but they'd take you where you could but - quite different of - years ago to what it is today. Mm. Quite different. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 When you were at school did you go out for walks by yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 It was just before - I left scho
ol that they started the nature study. And we went for walks, it was only - just started as I left school at fourteen, I remember going up to Blackmore End Road and I thought we should never - we was going to lose our way. We was after moss and anything w
e could find you see. That was just before I left school, and that's when I was fourteen. Mm. That was all really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 But you wouldn't go for a walk by yourself out of school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh no. No. No. No. Only - you know, just that at school. Unless we - sort
 of went from one friend's house to another, that was all. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 There was always a purpose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, there was a purpose to that, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
I asked you about - you told me about how your father gave up drinking and so on but I don't think I asked you whether your mother ever had a drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, she never had a drink, no. They used to make a lot - only home made wine, they used to make their own - home made wine and she'd have a glass of that just to try it. She never had no other drink 'cos s
he suffered with blood pressure. Mm. Mm. Well they call it blood pressure now but I don't know what they called it years ago.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
We were talking about the village as a whole and the way that different sorts of people treated each other, I was wondering whether there was anybody that you were expected to call sir at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh - always - you always had to call all the farmers sir, and - the squire, we used to have to go about and bob to them, if you met them in the road you had to bob to them. Sq
uire, and - his wife. And then there used to be the vicar and his wife. And the - farmers, they always used to raise - do like that to the farmers. Do like that. Salute to them. Yes. Salute to them. But the others you had to bob.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 So the farmers were really sort of half way people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. They were half way. You had to call them sir though. Had to call them sire when they were out - oh no sir or oh yes sir and - all like that, or thank you sir, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Would the schoolteacher be on the same sort of level as the farmer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh always had to say please teacher. Please teacher.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Not quite so important as the farmers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No, please teacher. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Did you feel as a schoolgirl that it was possible to move from one sort of social group to another or did you feel that people just sort of stayed in one station in life forever?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Well - they did - in them - days you see they never sort of go - well I had one uncle - but he - just - left the village like that, and his mother was upset, well
 he went in the police force but - you know, we just kept the same in the villages, yes, did really, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 There weren't people who got newly rich or something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, not those days, no. We had to save just a - penny at a time, you know, 
mother and father - a sixpence then was an awful lot you see or if you got - if you got a pound it was awful - you know, seemed an awful lot of money - to what it does of today. Yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You told me about when you married and so on, were you sort of
 formally engaged for quite a long time before you got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh no, I went out and - went out with one boy - and - for a little while, only just boy girl affair like and then - with my husband, I did go longer with him, I went nearly two years. I 
kept with him all the time. At first it was just boy and - girl thing you know, but with me husband I kept with him all the time, about two years. Then we got en - you know, engaged, and then I got married because me mother died you see and I was left alo
ne and me father - just with me father. He wanted to get married again so - of course we got married and then got married. He knew that I was all right and then he didn't mind.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 How long was it from when you got engaged to when you got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh
 I should say it was about - six months. Six months, yes. About that - that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Some people at that time seem to have had very long engagements.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh yes, some used to years ago, yes. Oh they used to have ever such long engagements some of them did. 
Yes. Yes, they did - but - then never got married. There was a boy here next door. Same age - well, not quite so old as I am, he was courting from the time the girl left school and he never did marry her. And he was - never did marry her, and he was court
i
ng her all that time. Yes. Then of course he moved from her and he went further on, but he's dead no but he - was not very old when he died, sixty - so he - you know, he just used to go up there and stay with her and - her house and - he never did marry h
er. Yes. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Did you find that once you started work it sort of changed your relationship with your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, not really because they were still got control over me then, they was not like of today. You had to do - even when you was working
 - you had to come home you half a day off if we was near home we always had to come home. My father always seen me in at night. He used to bicycle home with me at night. 'Cos it was never sort of - left - without control. Not until you was twenty-one. Th
at's the year I married. That was, yes, but - oh yes, you had to report you know, and if you wanted anything done or anything - or - you had to take care of your money and all the rest of it you know. You - bought - bought anything that had to be just }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14953070\charrsid14840390 sort}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390  or - you see - you got into trouble. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Do you feel that starting work changed your attitude to life at all then?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No. No. You know, it was - just working and that and you felt - oh pro of yourself 'cos you was earning some money you see. Y
es. Without asking your mother and father for every - penny if you want - well, if you want anything. Mm. Yes. I was home - home from school about - for ever - oh for several week before I started work, well that seemed to drag on that did really, yes. An
d
 then - that was - mother said, oh you - got this little - job for me, day girl at half a crown a week and - 'cos you had to wait for the jobs that came along if you wanted - but the - schoolmaster wanted me to be a schoolteacher but I didn't want to be a
 schoolteacher.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You wouldn't have preferred something different then from what you did?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes, I - no, no, I just enjoyed being a - house - housemaid and - and that, and then I went - and the war just started you see, I - we - from the Manor there
 they had to get - hadn't a butler and one thing and another and the cook, she left and - and took on the cooking for a while after I - didn't go up and down London with them. And of course then I had to leave then and go home to my mother had a stroke an
d - had to look after her. So I was about two years - nearly two years at home before I married. Mm. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Did you feel when you were working that you and your employers had the same interests?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh yes, they took interest in you really. You know, f
or what you wore and that. Same as I was at the Manor, well in the wintertime we had black dresses - for the afternoon, we had black dresses and these little fancy - fancy aprons. Summer time we had grey dresses, and the aprons, that made just a bit of ch
a
nge. And she'd always buy that material but you had to have it made up yourself. To fit you you see. Used to have to go to Bardfield to have it made. Yes, that was the nearest dressmaker. Yes. We had to be just so in the house with all these white collars
,
 stiff collars right up to here, and cuffs to here this width you see. And your hair and a cap on your head. One day Lady Flannery come home - I didn't expect her home and I was busy cleaning brass in the dining room, and - she came in, Candler, she said,
 where's your cap? I said, oh, I forgot to put it on. I knew all the time I hadn't put it on. But if they was there or not you had to be dressed just the same. With your uniform on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You were saying it was your mother that got the job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, she go
t the job, yes. She got the job for me, I went down there days, I don't know how long I was - she was an actress, they used to come down to London, I used to go down and - just where the cat and the dog was you see, and - I - used to look after them. I wa
s there - about how long - about six months I suppose. Six months, something like that. And then she gave up the house and then I went home. And then - the next job -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Can we just stay on that one?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did she give you any sort of holidays or half days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, no. No, I used to - I didn't go down Sundays. Didn't go down Sundays. I used to work all the week but not Sundays. Unless they was - she was down at the weekend and then I used to have to go down on a Sunday. Yes. I did. She used to
 have two children, she'd got two children, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 She paid you half a crown?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Half a crown a week, that's all I had, from - seven - seven in the morning 'til - oh I don't know what time at night. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you give that to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 O
h - I saved that all up. First - yes - first of all I had to - I didn't used to sleep in, well then when the children got - so they - when they didn't come down I used to have to sleep down there you see, with her, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you never give any of the money to your mother then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh I used - yes, I used to get - well - not while I was day girl, not while I was day girl.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Later on you used to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
I - didn't used to give mother hardly anything, no. No, she didn't take no money away from me, no. 
No. I used to buy her little presents when I was out, but - only like something she'd like you know, but not to give her - she never took no money off of me, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Was there anyone else there when you were a day girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 I was the only one down there. Yes, I was the only one. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you eat separately there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Separately - ate 1 always ate separately, yes, always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Was there a kind of room where you could sit down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, in the kitchen. In the kitchen. Kitchen was our apartment
 in those days. But at the Manor we had the servants hall, what they called servants hall, a room by yourself you see, we used to eat, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What sort of food did she have, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What, the first job? Oh I had the same as them, they us
ed to have joints of meat, that's about the first - time I saw a joint of meat you know, and I - I use you have exactly the same as they had, yes. And I used to go straight home and tell my mother all about it you know. She used to do the cooking herself,
 
yes. I sort of done the house you know and the washing up, I done all the dirtiest of the work and as you might say. Yes. Yes, the food was very good, I mean if they had bought food or anything they always shared it with me. Yes. Always. Yes. So - I - I -
 where I've been to - I've - always had good food. Yes I have. They always treated - always treated us well with the food.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Was it always the same kind of food, joints and that kind of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, well there used to be game you see - pheasants and
 - yes. Yes. Fish. All like that, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You wouldn't have had that when you were a day girl though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No, no, didn't have so much like that as a day girl, no, 'cos you see they wasn't there so much, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 When you were a day girl did they ha
ve any musical evenings or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No. No. She used to be sort of learning - learning - and 1 as she was an actress you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 She read a lot I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, she read a lot, yes. She used to spend hours making herself up. Yes
. And then she used to have - she got a divorce I think from her husband and she - his name was Will Comp - Compton used to come down weekends you see, yes. Yes. 'Cos that's - good few years ago, he must be dead now, long enough ago, but there's still I h
ear sometimes a Will Compton about, whether he's a relation I don't know. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 And they had children you said?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, they had a boy and a girl, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did they play games with their children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, I used to play with those, they were nice
 children, yes, they was, nice \{ILLEGIBLE\}. Bobby was one name, the girl they used to call Bobby and the boy was Bruce. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 But you weren't really in charge of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh no, no, I used to - if they went out for the day I used to - be with 'em you see and look after 'em see that they ate their food all right and - but - the rest of it, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 But the parents really looked after them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh they looked after them, yes. Yes they did, yes. She'd got a house in London you see as well so she didn't always bring them down with her. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Would she have had a small staff up there in London?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
I suppose so, yes. Yes. Then when she come from Braintree station you see it used to take her some time, because she used to have to hire a pony an
d trap from the George Inn to get - so it used to take some little time from Braintree station. Yes. Then to go back again, 'cos there's no cars about then. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Do you remember how she was with her children, whether she was rather distant?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh n
o, she was very fond of them, very fond of them, yes she was, very fond of them. Yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did they say grace at meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Well I wasn't in the dining room you see, no, I wasn't in the dining room, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Do you know if they took any interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
I don't remember at the - not the first - job I had, no, the other jobs I did but not the first one. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Then you went on to Black Notley didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Black Notley, oh that was a hard job that was,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 How did you get that job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Well it was through the Marriott's at Abbots Hall you see, they - this was their son. And - they wanted a between maid you see and they come to my mother to see if I was available and - which I was and of course away I went. I They come and fe
tched me. And that's how I got that job, but I only stayed three months, that's more than I could stick.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 There was a parlourmaid, housemaid and cook housemaid as well as yourself?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 She - yes - she was a cook - sort of a cook nursemaid really she
 was because she used to take the child out in a pony cart - she - yes, above all - and I used to have to do all the - do most of her work you see, like that. Then I used to have to go and help the housemaid and - oh, between them it was - it was awful.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You didn't help her look after the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
I didn't - no, was only child, was only one child. It seemed such a funny do, a cook - cook nurse, she used to do the cooking - but I used to have to get it all ready you see, she used to take the - chi
ld out in the pony trap in the afternoon. That's all they had to look after - of courser their - the mother you see used to have it sometimes in the morning if the cook was - had got too much cooking to do. I shall never forget the - she made a pie ready 
f
or me to cook. And I begun to let it burn, didn't I go through it. Oh dear. Didn't I go through over that. Well, I said, I can't -do - I was doing for - doing this and doing that, I said, and I've got to watch the oven, I said, how could I keep on backwar
d
s and forwards. It was - you know, doing the steps one minute and then - doing the - upstairs, I had to go upstairs and help the housemaid make the beds and - then I was downstairs again, perhaps I'd be churning the butter, you know, with the churn. It wa
s a job, I said to my mother, I can't stick that, I - I'm coming home. So I only stopped three months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What sort of hours would that be then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh I was up - I was the first one up to light a big old range, that heated all the water, with ovens eac
h side you see. Black leaded, all black lead and steel, you had to keep all the steel just so and all this black leading and then had to do all the flues once a week. Well - I mean you was never done, was always at it. One day then she said to me she said
,
 I want you to learn - the table work now. So - I - said all right so I went one evening in the black frock, that was stand at the head of the table and watch the housemaid what she - did - she used to do and that, the houseparlourmaid I mean, and then - 
n
ext night she said, you come in again, well I hadn't finished work, I was still in me print frock, away I went in I come out the dining room quicker than I went in. 'Cos I wasn't in - in the black frock. Oh it was a hard job that was, she was a rather har
d woman she was, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 How did you get on with the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh - I - then I left there you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 How did you get on with the other people there I mean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh the cook - all right, she was all right to me, yes, she was all right, but - oh she - she wasn't - she used to make - oh such a lot of washing up doing anything you know, and I had a lot to do and the vegetables and - oh dear, it was a very ha}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13316472\charrsid14840390 rd}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390  place that was. I said I'd never go -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What time did you have to get up then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh I used to have to get up at six. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What time would you be allowed to go to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh it would be eleven by the time you've done at night. Yes. On the go - I never went out of that house, only to church twice in the three months I was there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Never had a half day or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No. No. No half day. I said I'd never go as between maid again, that was the worst job out that was. But mind you - I learnt a lot there. That's where had my learning you see, to help lay the table and - all the
 other different jobs you see, and then I went from there - yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What did she pay you, do you remember that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh - not much. I think I had about - ten shill - I don't know if I had ten shillings a month and me food. Yes. 'Cos the food counte
d those days you see. Yes - food counted a lot. But we had good food there, I will say that, we had all lovely new - butter, you know, farm butter, and we used to have plenty of milk to drink. Yes. We did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Was there a servants hall in that place,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, only a kitchen. Just the kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You could go and sit down there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes. I think I can see the sink in the scullery now, it was nearly as long as this couch. Oh it was a horrible stone sink. Yes. Yes, all be washing up piled up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did the mistress supervise the work personally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did she tell the cook what to do and then the cook would tell you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
She used to come to me very often but she'd mostly tell the cook, but - the other - the cook would be on to me in the kitchen
 you see, well when I went the other part of the house I used - she used to sort of - get on to me and tell me what to do. Yes. And then the housemaid would as well, she would say what to do. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 That was the first time you were away from home so we
re you rather homesick there or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Well I think I was really a little bit homesick there. Yes, 'cos you see I couldn't get out. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You didn't have time to think very much though I shouldn't think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. Terrible place that was. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What about the family there, did they have musical evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No. Nothing at all, no. No. No. We just had - if we did get a spare minute we'd have a book and read, but we never saw a newspaper there even. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did the master and mistress read though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
They used to read, they used to read, yes, but - there was nothing musical there at all, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 And games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No - well they used to go out play tennis. Used to play tennis and go out shooting and that but that was all. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Was there grace at meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, not there, no. On the prayers, we had to go in to prayers every morning at a certain time. And - Mr Marriott used to say the prayers and we had to kneel with him - yes, while he said the prayers. Every morning that was, w
e didn't have 'em at night, only in the morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Was he interested in politics at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes, he was rather, yes. Yes, a bit. 'Course there was - if it - if there'd been an election on you see I should have heard more but as there was no election on you see I didn't hear quite so much, no. Election time, that's when politics were on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 He was a Conservative?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, he was a Conservative, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You said that he took part in sports?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, in shooting and that, yes, shooting, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did he go to the races,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, I don't remember, no. He used to have a horse - but he didn't go to races, he used to go hunting you see. Hunting but not - he didn't go to races, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did he play cards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Don't remember him playing ca
rds, no, no, no, they didn't no. 'Cos they were very religious family, they didn't play cards, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did he belong to a club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, I don't think he did, no. No, don't think - don't remember, see I was only there three months. No. Yes, I don't remember him - belonging to a club. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Do you remember the mistress going out on her own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh yes, she used to go out on her own in - a pony and trap you see, and - they didn't always go together but - very often they would go together to see the; pa
rents at Abbots Hall, Shalford you see, 'cos they was the family you see, or else she used to come here to Wagsfield place to see her mother and father, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 When she went out it was calling really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh - they didn't go round the village a lot. N
o. Yes. Now at the Man - oh that was another place though the Manor they used to go a lot round the village. Mm. To the poor. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 He didn't actually have an occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, he was just independent. Yes, just independent, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Would he go away to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} for long periods?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Don't think so, not while I was there he did - I don't remember him going, no. No. Used to like his garden. He used to like his garden, he'd like his garden, yes. 'Cos they had a good - they used to have a man - odd man
 used to see after the horse and the garden and that. Man used to have pump all the water up for the house, used to have a well and you have to do it by hand like this, pump all the water up for the house. Now it's all done by electricity isn't it \{
ILLEGIBLE\}. I don't know what they'd think of today. Yes, that well used to be outside the back door I can see it going round and round now - - used to - turn this handle then he'd stand a minute. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did they entertain very much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, a good bit, ye
s, they did, yes, of a evening used to have people to dinner you see at night, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What sort of people would come?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Well they'd be their - like their own - the farmers and - all their own - relations you see would come 'cos there was a - Gordons
, they were a - biggish family I think, about two, three, four I think of the Gordons there was and then there was several of the Marriots as well and they used to be backwards and forward to each other. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What about calling in the afternoon, would people call in and leave cards?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Well - not very - no, not very much at that place they didn't call, no. No, not very much. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Was that more a {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} thing do you think then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Beg pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You think you saw more of that in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh yes, at the Manor House they had a lot more of that than when I was at the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Why do you think there were fewer people there then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
I don't know why - they - if they didn't make friends or there's not many here you see, Black Notley
 was a small place then you see, very small. Of course it's all built up now but it was very small when I was there. Yes. Very few people. Mm. Built right up to there now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did they give any of these friends more elaborate dinners?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh yes. Yes, t
hey was more - sort of more elaborate, now - got out everything of the silver you know, they used to have silver theirselves but of course everything was got out when they had visitors. Had everything the best 'cos otherwise some of - it was locked up.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Even for the farmers?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh yes, anybody they would have - they - yes, yes. Special china you know for the teas and that, yes, to what they had theirselves, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 How did guests behave towards you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh - oh they used to - some - guests used 
to be very nice and others would just - look at you like that, but - most of 'em was - very nice and say thank you very much when they went - out, and goodbye and that you know, and - sometimes they'd tip a - something in your hand, sometimes they didn't 
you know. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Mr Marriot wasn't ambitious really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 To kind of make a mark in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No, he wasn't - ambitious in any way, no, only just done his little - job, you know, with his garden and that but - not - I never known him to do any work. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 A very retiring sort of person really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes, he was, yes, very retiring, yes. Very retiring. He was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 After that you went on to Wickham Bishops didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. That was - that was the sister of this Marriot at Wickham Bishops.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 That was the vicar wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Yes, that was the vicar. That was very - she was very nice, quite different to what the brother was. And - they did want me to stay on but I - I went there for six weeks. You see, it was - nobody 
I knew there you see, and she did so beg of me to stay on but I said, no, it's too far from home. Couldn't get home you see. And - so I just left, but oh she was - she said, I do wish you'd stay, but - I said, no. She said, I've never had anybody do my ho
use like it, and wait at table and all. I said, I learnt it from your brother. 'Cos I learnt it from there. Well then I left there you see. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What exactly did you have to do while you were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh I was - house parlourmaid. House parlourmaid
. Because there was all lamps, all they - sort of things, in all the rooms they had a lamp every room, you had to do all them. And then used to take 'em tea up in bed - in the morning and then used to - wait at the - get the breakfast, wait at - clear awa
y, and then used to do all the bedrooms, and then used to \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 the lunch and wait on the lunch and then clear away and then there was - odd jobs in the afternoon I couldn't get done in the morning because I was cleaning silver and - that. And then I 
used to get the tea, and then after tea - they didn't have much for tea, just cup of tea and - if anybody come they'd have a laid out tea, well then of course at night was dinner. They nearly always had a parson or - somebody come for dinner you know. Onc
e
 they had thirteen parsons there for dinner. Thirteen. And it thundered and it lightened and it came down, the hailstones were as big as that. The greenhouses were all broken. Never shall forget that night. Never. The cook was busy you see as well, she wa
s
 busy. Quite enjoyed being there but it was lonely because I got nobody I knew - we did go out - she did let you out for half a day - and Sundays, we didn't have to do very little on a Sunday there. In fact, hardly anything, only just the bare necessities
 on a Sunday. So that was quite - a - a change you see, that was. M
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 All the other places you had to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, I had to work, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What time did you have to get up there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh about half past six. About half - about half past six, yes, 
of course the co used to do the fireplace and that then, I didn't do that 'cos I was the - the other parlourmaid -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 So it was shorter hours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, shorter hours, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Would you be in bed before eleven then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh yes, yes, we did, yes
. Yes. Very nice - they were very nice, I was very comfortable but I tell you it was so far from home. Now the cook - she had got a - bicycle but my mother wouldn't let me have my bike there you see, to bike all that way home alone. And the cook used to c
ome to - bike ride home to Shalford you see, and back again, but it's more than I dare do, my mother and father wouldn't let me do that, in case anything happened to me on the road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Do you remember what you were paid there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 I was paid - oh - about - five bob a week I think it was there. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 So better pay too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Was there a servants hall there or just the kitchen?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Well it was a - it was like a - a servants hall, there was the kitchen and then there was an other 
little room off, so that we had - we could sit in there - off from the kitchen. Yes, it was - really nice, it was a vicarage you see. Yes. And the gardener's wife used to ask me to tea there sometimes on a Sunday, she felt sorry for me so I used to go to 
the gardener's wife for tea. Yes. That was about every other Sunday that would be. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did they call you by your surname there too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You were never called by your Christian name?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No, no, no, they always called you by your surname, yes, always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 As a vicar I suppose he was quite a reader too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh yes. Yes, he was, always prayers, strict prayers there morning and night of course, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did he have a sort of library?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh he had a big library, yes. Big library. His room, you see, yes. Yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Would they have any musical evenings, hymn singing, anything like that in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No. If they had anything they went out - you know, same as at the school - and that and - he used to - or Sunday sc
hool and that he used to have you see. We didn't have a - we didn't have no children up at the house, no, that was all done out - outside. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did they play any games at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh tennis. Tennis.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 They wouldn't play cards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No. No. Used to play tennis.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Would he take any part in hunting, riding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No. No. No, never, no. He used to have - a cart - a pony and cart to go about in but they never took part - in anything like that, you see, they used to - used to go round visiting well they'd have the pony and - cart then. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did his wife go out visiting separately?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. They - yes, they used to both go out together and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Visiting the poor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes. Yes, they did, yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 I think you said that she didn't do any work for charities though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No. Just visited people, that's all, yes. Just visiting. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Sometimes they'd go out together would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, they mostly went out together, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 So she wasn't really a sort of
 independent clergyman's wife who would do a lot of work on her own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, no, she wouldn't do anything if she could help it. All left to us to do. You know, she'd come out in the kitchen you know and give her orders what she wanted and that was that f
or the day, yes. She left it to you all the time. Yes. If there's anybody coming to tea or dinner she'd just tell you you see and have - you've got to have everything ready just so. Yes. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Were they interested in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No. Not while I was there any rate, no. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 They had grace at meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did they have daily family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh yes. Yes, morning and night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 And evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 And evening too, yes. Always, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 And you all had to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
We had to go, yes, in together, yes, we was all in together, yes. They were very nice, both of 'em was very nice, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you sing a hymn then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, only prayers. Just prayers. Just prayers. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 And the entertaining was almost entirely clergymen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Mostly was clergymen, yes. Yes. Clergymen, yes. 'Cos at that place too there was - that was a small village you see and there's not many - able to come. No. No.-
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 I'm surprised he didn't entertain any parishioners though.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, we d
idn't have any - many up at the house at all, no, they used to go round but - not while I was there, no. No. Didn't, no. If there was anybody who - wanted anything they'd come up and ring the bell and I used to have to - show 'em in his study or room you 
see and then - of course they was talking to theirselves you see, I - that was my job and that was - all I knew, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 He had a lot of people who used to come round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Used to come to him if they wanted any advice or - anything you see, yes. And you know used to have to go wherever he was and ask him was it convenient you see to see so and so, if it wasn't he'd say no and - they - they'd have to go again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did he spend a long time writing his sermons?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes, that's right, yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 After that you went to the hall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 The Hall.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You hardly told me about that at all, what exactly were you doing there?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
I was - house parlourmaid there, houseparlourmaid. I - don't know how long I was there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 About two months you said?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Something like that, yes, and then the war broke out you see and - then he had to go - to the war then she gave up the home, yes. But that - that place, Porters Hall, my father always used to - see that I was in the house at night, he wouldn't let 
me go along there, it was about - five - six or seven miles I suppose from Shalford.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 You didn't live in there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
He - I used to let me bike home you see alone but he - he'd always see that - I was in the house, yes. But sometimes I used to dodge him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Were you living at home then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, I was living at Porters Hall. And - he used to see me home you see and - 'course I was - getting used to the - the cook's brother then was - little bit - fond of me or - boy and girl sort of boy and girl to
gether, well I used to - my father used to - see me in - felt I'd gone right into the house but of course - used to play truant, out I'd come again and meet this boy. So we was just a bit a bad some - sometimes them days as they are now. If my father knew
 about it he'd give me a good hiding. Yes. Well then you see I left - they were - they were nice, they were - he was a captain in the - \{BLANK\}
 I think he was captain in, and there was a moat right round the house, that was a very nice house, and that, but of course I wasn't there long but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 How many other people were there there then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Just the cook. Cook, yes. Just a cook, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did you have your own sort of servants hall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. Yes, we did, yes, we had our own little servants hall there
, and the food was very good there too. Because that was a farmhouse that was you see. Had plenty of eggs and milk and butter and that, and - yes, and then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What sort of hours did you have to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Oh just ordinary - like I did at the - other place, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What time off did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
We had a half a day in the week and every other Sunday. Yes. Every other Sunday. But I didn't always go home in the week because - it was for me father to come back with me, I - you know, he would - but - i
f I did go home I had to go home before dark. 'Cos he was working you see. Yes. 'Cos that used to take about threequarters of an hour and - to an hour to get home you see on your bicycle, so long, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Do you remember what you were paid there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 I
 think I was paid about seven and six a week there. Yes, seven and six a week. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 She sort of supervised the work herself did she?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, she did, yes. She supervised, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 How did you get on with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 She was all right - yes, s
he was all right, but a bit - hoity-toity you know and yes. Different to what - Mrs Marriot - Mrs Shuttleworth was over at Wickham Bisha. Yes, you know, she was like this, she'd got children, got grown up children. Yes, she had, they only used to come hom
e for schooldays. Yes. Forget how many they was, two or three I think, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Did she mind what you did in your own time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh no, she - no, never mind - her never troubled, but you had to be in at the certain time you see. Ten o'clock, no later than ten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 She didn't feel she ought to give you kind of moral guidance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes. She - we had to be in at ten sharp. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Obviously you weren't lonely there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What about the housework there, who mended the clothes and so on?
