Well - the sheets and that were sent out, some of the washing we used to have to do at home but not a lot. No, that was sent out. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Was that the same as the previous places?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes, just the same, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 They didn't have a washerwoman coming in to help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No. No. No. All the places I've been to - the washing has been pu
t out, except - some - the ladies maid used to have to do some special - clothes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 And the only place where there was a needlewoman was the last one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
The Manor. At the Manor, yes, she used to do all the needlework and used to make their nighties and - all sorts of things. Even the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14953070\charrsid14840390 chair covers}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390  she'd make. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What about tinned food at these houses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
Oh they never had tinned food. No. Soup - was all the same with soup, they used to make the soup, there's always a - big - like an urn on t
he - big range you see and that was always bones was in here and they was kept on so long and that was strained off and - and that, then they had fresh bones again from the butchers you see. But they used to make all their own soups yes. It was all put th
rough a sieve if they made pea soup or - artichoke soup, it was all put through - that was a job that was, putting it all through these sieve by hand with a spoon you see. They used to be nice thought, jolly nice it used to be. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 None of these places had a gas cooker?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 
No, it was always coal. Yes. But even at the Manor we used to have it come straight from the mine - to the Manor. Yes. Yes. 'Cos they wanted such a lot you see, a big house like that. Mmm. Well, up at the Manor we did have gas ligh
t. Gas light. But it was done with - Calor - carbide. Carbide. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What about sort of home foods, you baked bread at the Manor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 Would the other places have baked their own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8743498 AG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 No, they never baked it, no. It was only dur
ing the - just at the beginning of the war you see when you couldn't get - the bread that they baked the bread, yes. Otherwise it was - after the - that they never - baked the bread. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2896308 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3175380\charrsid14840390 What about jam, would most of them make their own jam?
